Use hand jams to climb the left leaning crack
Climb the face the face on the right end of the warm up wall.

name: Alarm Clock
description: Sit start with wide hands, head up using face holds, features, and holds just around the arete. Really nice problem, consistently tough moves and super solid rock except for the slightly hollow rock capping the boulder. The block on the right is off.

name: Gold Star for Robot Boy
description: Left hand up the arete, R hand up the face. Top out at the peak.

name: Jump out of Bed
description: Start matched on the ledge with good feet and dyno to the top of the boulder.

name: Morning Stretch
description: Start matched on the huge ledge in the middle of the face and then work to the right on good crimps towards the top.

name: Pull My Finger
description: Sit Start. Start on right side of “Warm Up Wall” and traverse left until you come to thin crack. Top out at crack. Start begins with rightmost Sloper on wall. Topping out before crack is off problem.  Video of First Assent youtu.be/s0BkROfRRBs

name: Arrow Head (Far Left)
description: The first 30 foot vertical start requires stepping up onto the starting block then using small pockets and mid-finger depth side pulls to move through a well defined 9 sequence. Mantle up and to the right to top out the first section. Roughly 15 feet of 5.2 ascends a ramp band section of chert. A section of 5.5 moves to top out. Rap anchors provided a the top, just below the lip.

name: Chubb Roof Traverse
description: Traverse under the roof from One for Dunning to Poop Shoot.  It is possible to continue bouldering all the way to the Chubb Trail Crack start. The problem is a bit harder and require a bit more repeated cleaning. This is a nice diversion on a rainy day or while waiting your turn to climb.

name: Chubb Trail Crack
description: This continuous crack sucks up pro so take a range of cams, nuts and what ever else you fancy. The crux is getting started and mellows after you are 10 feet off the ground. A slightly easier start involves several face moves just left of the base of the crack. This may feel more like a 5.7 crux for people who feel more comfortable with face climbing.

name: Commuter
description: Crux is the last 15 feet of the climb, between the last bolt and the two bolt anchor. Steep face with pockets transitions to a roof bulge with a reach. The route gets it's name from the fact that someone can move right and finish the climb on Chubb Trail Crack to avoid the crux.

name: Deathly Hollows
description: Fun route that starts under an overhang. Pull through the roof (crux) and up through some interesting pockets. Climbing eases off as you move through some ledges. Pull through the last roof to reach the anchors. If your planning on top roping this, make sure you bring something long enough to extend your anchor over the edge.  This line was only slightly cleaned and first climbed for the great pocketed boulder crux at the beginning then ran out a bit on small pro. Thank Andrew for all his cleaning and bolting effort. Enjoy the now well protected classic.

name: Geranium Mine
description: This pocketed line is just right of Chubb Trail Crack. The easy start option involves using the beginning of the Chubb Trail Crack then heading right to the first bolt and up past many pockets and a hand full of bolts to a two bolt rap anchor. Harder start begins directly under the route and slightly right of the first bolt, pulling on pockets to manage your way over the low roof. Boulder problem crux feels like a 10+ move and is a bit reach dependent.

name: Hawt Hueco
description: Cruise through the first two bolts on the pocketed face and be rewarded at the third bolt by this route's namesake. The crux move is getting over the small roof ahead. Skip the fifth bolt and push for the anchors if you want a spicy option with 15+ feet of run-out, or play it safe and clip the fifth.

name: One for Dunning
description: One for Dunning is one of the first routes you find on the right end of the Chubb Crack Wall. Two different starts effect the route's rating dramatically depending on starting directly below the first bolt or just down and right of the first bolt. this rating is based on the easier start just right of the bolt. Climb up then step left to use a pocket to clip the first bolt. Continue to the next bolts and rap anchors at the top.

name: One for Dunning (Direct Start)
description: Two different starts affect the route's rating dramatically depending on starting directly below the first bolt or just down and right of the first bolt. This rating is based on the harder start just direct below the first bolt.

name: Poop Chute
description: Poop  Chute has an interesting start at the lower roof and dihedral crack. use a hand jam with the right and palm press with the left. Safety bolts are in place. Belayers should wear a helmet.

name: Salamander
description: Fairly straightforward face climb, follow the bolts to the anchor.  The crux is right before the third bolt. It's possible to traverse to the left before the crux but a fall would be bad. This route has a lot of potential but it needs significant cleaning first.

name: Bouquet
description: Start with right hand on large diagonal crimp as pictured with lower left hand to start. The loose rock is off.

name: Corkscrew
description: Climb the twisting rightward trending crack protecting as you go. The top out is pretty dirty, make sure to protect it well.

name: Decanter
description: To the left of Oak Barrels

name: Devil's Den
description: This is a high ball. Please approach with extreme caution. Please use at least 4 pads. Starts with hands matched sit start. The arete is off

name: Devil's Detour
description: Getting to the last big jug to top out

name: Doors of Durin
description: Straight up

name: Feature Film
description: Super easy climb but the features are really neat. Sitstart on left facing jug. Head straight up toward sloppy rails and cool pinch feature.

name: Fermentation
description: Tall top out. Careful when spotting

name: Jim would be Proud
description: First non slab route

name: Jim Would Be Right
description: The right exit to “Jim Would Be Proud”. Same start and first few moves, but topout to the right instead of to the left. Avoids the traverse.

name: MO'scato
description: To the right of Jim Would be Proud

name: Oak Barrels
description: The crux is the flat top finish. Please clean the top and be careful.

name: Reserve
description: Crux is around the middle. The back wall is within the falling zone so YOU MUST STACK TWO PADS AGAINST THE WALL. Please be careful.

name: Rohr like a lion
description: Short problem. Start with feet underneath. Hold self up and pull feet to right. Heel hook and make your way up

name: Scotty Knows
description: Avoid the arete. Careful.

name: Tannin Crack
description: Up the hill from the welcome boulder. Find the excellent crack around the left corner of the tall face

name: The Taste of Sandstone Wall
description: Climb starting on the steps and traversing up to the left.This wall has many different routes.Starting on the left going up:       Using the left boulder without the right is a V1-2       Using both is a V1Starting on the stairs:        Traversing using both boulders Right to left is a V2        Skipping the arete arete until the far left without.              using the neighboring boulder is a V3        Skipping to the second arete top out is a v1-2        Going straight up the steps is a V0

name: Valvin "No Hands" Muscat
description: Make your way up the steps without using your hands. Try to make your way back down for an added "high five" bonus.

name: Wine a Little
description: Starts low on the 2 yellow circles

name: Wine-Jazz
description: Start low on the jugs. The top is a large jug.

name: Aged Five Years
description: The crux is the upper sloper and hitting the top out hold.

name: Airbags and Crashpads
description: Middle Crux, nice top out. Starts with match on sloper

name: Cyn city
description: Start sitting below Norton's cyn on under cling and crimp. Find usuable feet then travel either left as of the beta picture or finish on Nortons cyn grades are the same.

name: Das Ist Schnee Von Gestern
description: Runs along the arete

name: Fass hersteller
description: Starts near das ist schnee von gestern and works slightly right

name: Full Bodied
description: Crux is at the middle and topping out. You're going to have to brush and chalk the rail due to the recently disturbed top soil.

name: Norton's cyn
description: It is a slab route with a very high left foot start. but the route can be modded with the tree next to it.

name: Port
description: Start low work your way up to the ledge. Match heel (red dot) to hand and reach up

name: Top Rack
description: From sit start, move to jug finish above the sit start.Best route for pictures.Alternative route: from the sit start, move to the crimp just to the right of top rack

name: Babe Crack
description: Climb the crack

name: Backdraft
description: SDS as per Rosin but traverse low and right towards a right facing hold into Sterno. Then climb as per Sterno and continue right to end on Blazin.

name: Blazin
description: SDS as per Rosin but traverse right on the slopey top and finish as per Sterno.

name: DITCOE
description: Sit start on Fire and then do a cool gaston sequence to transition into the start of Backdraft and then finish as per Backdraft. I thought "Firestarter" would've been a cool name for this, but for reasons unknown, "DITCOE" stuck...

name: Dog Ear
description: It's the center offwidth in the middle of the three cracks.

name: Faces
description: Climb the face using the obvious edges. Several variations exist

name: Fire
description: Sit-start with and undercling and a sidepull and continue up the arete.

name: Firsty
description: Start to the right of the tree. Follow jugs to the top

name: Gridlock
description: Start with a left facing hold and make a long move to a good hold.

name: Heat
description: Start on edge at head-level. Go to rounded top-out.

name: Hope
description: Climb huge jugs and have fun topping out. It gets interesting up there

name: Kaya
description: Start in the corner and go up to the left facing flake(dog ear shaped). Do the sketchy top out.

name: Last Picnic
description: Not in the Mo’ Beta Guidebook or on MP. We were shown this route by some fellas from St. Louis. Please change the name if I got it wrong!  Start on obvious jugs on the right arete and work up left. Instead of going for the sloper rail (as in Tablecloth), go up for the big pinch. Move up and top out from there.

name: Old School
description: Climb the face

name: Paul Bunyan Crack
description: Work your way up the crack

name: Picnic
description: Start with a high edge for the left hand and jump to a good crimp. Move out to finish on Tablecloth.

name: Rosin
description: Sit-start with a positive left-facing hold and climb up the slopey seam.

name: The Scary One
description: Left Facing offset crack. Climb up. A little sketchy.

name: The Shadow
description: Sit-start low and climb 3/4 of the way up to a crimp and top out on the arete.

name: The Slabby One
description: Climb the slabby face.

name: Slow Ride
description: Slab moves all the way up.

name: Spooky
description: Climb up the less than vertical face with a right facing flake. Go all the way up, toping out as high as you can.

name: Sterno
description: Start in a big jug under a roof and traverse right.  Finish with a really cool mantel on a unique hold.  Fun, unique moves and good rock make this a great problem.

name: Tablecloth
description: SDS or not, SDS is a bit harder but fun. Move to a left crimp on the face and then top out left of the apex.

name: The Tennishoe Crack
description: The V-shaped dihedral. Do it with tennis shoes on!

name: Attie Cave Crack
description: Within a canyon separating the Junebug boulder from its left neighbor is a fun, hidden beginner finger crack. Same basic quality and difficulty as the tennis shoe crack down front, but this will be a less busy. For a newer partner, the opportunity to leave the problem by stemming the canyon may make it feel less exposed and committing.

name: Bookstore Blues
description: Begin from a seated position, follow the arete up and right to the top of the arete

name: Crystal Method Slab
description: Climb this steep slab using the small/sharp crystals

name: Erica's Edge
description: Climb up and left with the sharp arete.

name: The Finger Crack
description: Small crack that works up the middle of the boulder.    Hard feet placement.

name: Flake Slab
description: Climb the slab by mantling on flexible flake

name: Forgotten Face
description: Start high on edges and hike your hands through long moves to reach the top

name: Junebug
description: Low start. Bear hug the double arete up.

name: Mono Arete
description: Climb the arete

name: One Way
description: With hands set left in crack and right in mono fire to the top

name: Picnic Fist Crack
description: An easy crack with a good landing. It trends rightward, and runs hands low to a perfect fist jam up high. A good low-commitment beginner crack

name: The Right Way
description: Climb up the right side of the arete

name: Thumbdercling Slab
description: Climb a featureless slab using the thumb undercling

name: Bigfoot
description: Start on jugs in the horizontal crack. Go up the arete to the right.

name: Bigfoot Traverse
description: Start on Bigfoot, traverse the crack left.

name: Extra Cheese
description: Climb through the tall flaring crack to the left of the dihedral

name: Fisting
description: Nice crack with a variety of jams available.

name: For My Children's Children
description: Front Range, in front of the Ananconda Boulder. If you are facing Vector Days the climb is behind you to the right.

name: Greenhouse
description: Climb subtle edges and crystals up the face.

name: Jump Start Thing
description: Dyno to the lip followed by a mantle for the finish

name: Knob Job
description: Climb the slab using the black crystal

name: The Lightning cracks
description: Climb through the cool looking zig zag crack system

name: Turtle traverse
description: This problem might not be much to look at, but it's actually quite fun.  Very hard V6 in my opinion.  It takes some effort to work the beta out, there's some funky moves on this one.    Start matched on the big black sloper on the left side of the boulder.  Move into the obvious sidepull to the right, avoiding the holds on the lip.  Use some combination of brute strength and technique to keep moving right, and make a big move out right to a sloper on the lip.  Top out when you can.

name: V4
description: Start matched on the right-facing scoop jug and head up.

name: Vector Days
description: Sit start on a pair of crimps. Work up the face making interesting moves on sidepulls and gastons.

name: BVD (aka It's Over)
description: Grab a high right-facing jug flake and move upward on decent holds to a committed topout. There is a tough sit start.

name: Consciousness
description: Start with left pinch/crimp and right crimp and go straight up. A couple hard moves lead to an easy but lichen-y topout.

name: Destined To Forget
description: Don't forget it

name: Fen
description: Start on jugs and work up the aerie

name: Jamboree
description: Sit start low and deep in the crack, hand jam you way out to eventually lying back the finish    V1 variation: Skip the hand jam and simply lay the crack back to the finish

name: Jumping Jim
description: Dyno and hita crystal edge in the middle of the wall. Have fun with the hand foot match for the finish

name: The Layback Crack
description: The classic warm up at the porch. Layback the crack and use the finger buckets to mantle out

name: Mission Control
description: High start using gastons, head up and right using crimps to the rounded top out

name: Shish Kabob
description: Sit start and go up the arete and onto the slab to the right. Those without the length to reach the jug from a true sit may have to use some funky tactics to do the start (recommended even for those who do have the reach, it's fun!). Know your downclimb!

name: Smoke
description: Start on the horizontal shelf, climb around the bulge and to the top

name: Smoke It
description: Begin on Fen and traverse left into Smoke

name: Gill Crack
description: Battle to get into the large offwidth crack then scrap your way up the highball boulder. (Know your down climb)

name: Barndoor
description: Sit start on a low jug, move up and right through cool holds and unusual moves. Topping out the boulder is possible but not entirely recommended; there's an obvious stopping point on a ledge, and while the climb the rest of the way to the top isn't hard the downclimb is pretty tenuous.

name: Scary Mary
description: Sit start on an overhang and jugs through fun, bouldery moves to a very blank slab. Absolutely exhilarating feeling to stick that top hold. It’s a beautiful climb.

name: Karpowitz Snapper
description: Start on high knob and move straight up.

name: Levitation Layback
description: Follow the crack up with bad feet to a slightly better layback hold before the committing finish to the rail.    v5 with a sit start.

name: No Way Out
description: Crux is near the top. Head up the layback and crack, then left to jams. Continue up and left for the top out. Originally climbed with a top rope, then lead with pro before bouldering (solo).

name: The North Remembers (Rump Rider)
description: One the backside of the obviously elephant shaped boulder- find a left hand sloper and right hand slopey crimp and low feet to start...traverse right & move upwards to the left hand side press and ride the rump to top out

name: Warden of the North
description: Find yourself with just enough room for the right hand finger tips in the first slot hold The sit start requires some strength and tricky feet to figure out which lead into a short finessed foot-puzzle before the top out. DONT BREAK THE FLAKE even it does feel satisfying to hold. Stand start with some slotted hold probably a V2.

name: Sitting Stoned
description: See map and photos for details

name: Trojan Man
description: Crouch start with hands on small crimps, top out center of the boulder

name: Jaws
description: First, admire the communal work of man and mother nature. Next, get psyched. Work up the man cut perfect finger flake from the ground to a chiseled ledge between the head wall and overhanging boulder. Traverse left to the roof boulder's crack using natural jibs or the drilled holes for feet. Work into the crack with a heel/feet on the ledge. Power up, through, and over the crack's thin holds and jams for a high ball top out on questionable blocks. Sustained line with a broad mix of technique and gumption.

name: Beezy's Bungle
description: Sit start in the hip-height pockets down low. Work out to leftmost and pull up to the little roof and mantle using good holds beyond the lip and a high foot to top out.

name: Pig in a Pocket
description: Jugs up from the sit start, use the 2 finger pocket to reach the lip over the bulge.

name: Wags' Bowl
description: Use the two sit start pockets low at the center of the boulder and head to the right arete up to the huge bowl jug above the lip of the roof.

name: Muscle up
description: Start matching on the really good sloper and dino to the top.

name: Beginner Chimney
description: Use a combination of crack climbing and stemming to reach the top

name: Euthanasia
description: Climb the face using pocketed edges and continue to the crack. Climb the crack up and right to top out.

name: Gong Show
description: Climb the flake feature using both the crack and face

name: Six Pack Crack
description: Crack climb the Johnson Shut-Ins classic!

name: New Beginning
description: Water continually shifts the pebble bank and varies in level through the year. Summer seems to be the best time to send this problem. A standing start is an easier warm up option.

name: Dihedral
description: Climb the amazing dihedral formation and build an anchor at the top.

name: Electric Green Bikini
description: This is the route that climbs the buttress just to the right of the observation deck. The 5.7 Dihedral is to the left. The crux is getting off the ground. Face and crack climb to the top. A fun climb for sure.

name: Arch Support
description: Use the face and small dihedral crack to reach the obvious horizontal crack. From there angle up and left to build an anchor

name: Beginner Chimney
description: Climb the crack and enter the chimney. Layback and stem you way up.

name: Cracadile
description: Follow the aerie into the dihedral and continue up the arete.

name: Waylayed
description: Climb the face using broken flakes and other edges.

name: Funky Slide
description: Low start on good holds, follow the stack of quarry rocks using the arete(s).

name: Liking Lichen
description: Small slabbish boulder covered in lichen. Sit start with wide hands, make your way up the face in a few moves and mantle to the top.

name: COVID crack
description: Sit start, either layback or use small crimps on the adjacent faces to work your way up the crack and top out.

name: Quarry Crimpin
description: Sit start, use small crimps to work up the middle of the face and top out.

name: Say No To Crack
description: Sit start, use crimps to ascend face left of the crack. Crack is off.

name: Obervation Deck Scramble
description: Scramble up and down the path of least resistance from the observation deck.  Its a quicker way to walk off the routes on the Main Wall. Easy scrambling just watch out for all the loose rock.

name: Quarantine Cove
description: Chose your line up the face at the back of the shallow alcove.  The crux is finding solid hands and feet while avoiding choss.  There is good rock you just have to search for it a bit.  When finished either downclimb or top out and scramble back down by the Observation Deck. This route should get much better with time.

name: Stepping to the Light
description: Climb the series of ledges working up and to the left. Crux is the mantle to top out then scramble down by the observation deck.

name: Bird is the word
description: Sit start on good crimp, bump left hand up and traverse around the boulder, utilizing the arete feature. Then mantle. Solid couple feet of easy climbing.

name: Highlands Slide
description: Climb the left side of the low angle face on this freestanding block. This one is all about the friction, avoid the blasting grooves to the right side of the face.

name: Mantlecore
description: Sit start on matched crimps, reach up and back for a high right hand, get high feet then power through the mantle to finish

name: Unknown
description: Super hard route through the left side of cave.

name: Gateway Drug (aka No. 41)
description: Follow the hand traverse, cut straight up when you can. Protect when necessary.

name: Keep on the Sunny Side (aka No. 44)
description: Follow the wicked crack placing gear when necessary, build anchor at the top.

name: Old School (aka No. 43)
description: Climb the edges of the face protecting when necessary. Build an anchor at the top.

name: Golden Hour Traverse (aka No. 55)
description: A strong contender for best lead at the Millstream Gardens.    Climb the rightward angling crack. Follow it until you interest route 58. Climb to the top from there. a Millstream Gardens classic.

name: Pine Nut (aka No. 51)
description: Climb the easy crack and place gear when necessary

name: Rock Chuck (aka No. 52)
description: Climb the easy crack and protect when necessary

name: Shady Grove (aka No. 53)
description: Climb the easy crack and protect when necessary

name: Acres of 9
description: 70M rope recommended. 60 meter rope optional if you rap from the first set of rap anchors, 15 feet below the lip of the cliff. A slightly overhanging start, on the lower face, leads to a nice big ledge. An easier, secondary start follows slab, left of the first few bolts, to the ledge above. A crux overhanging V0 (10b) boulder problem gets you off the ledge, by keeping you slightly right of the bolt. Use of a left heel hook, two intermediate slopers follows by jugs that are level with the next clip. An optional second beta breaker V0- (5.8+) bypass keeps you slightly left of the bolts, requiring a high reach to gain a sloper and jugs left of the next clip. From there, fairly sustained climbing alternates from vertical to slightly less-than-vertical, and finishes with a nice exposed step up to the anchors. The second set of anchors, at the top of the line, is slightly out of sight but up and left.

name: B Garden
description: CLOSED active bee hive above. Colder weather can change conditions through the winter. Cleaning required.70M rope recommended. Feel free to climb this line as a single pitch if you're using a 70M rope or a double rope system.P1: The first pitch of this tall line starts on a section of light colored rock, below the first tan colored bolt, then follows a slab of vertical edged formations, just left of Bee Hive. Follow the slab to the first small ledge and alcove, at the next section of light colored rock. A short climb up the right side of this feature gets you to the first rap anchors. 5.6, 50ftP2: The second pitch starts from the belay anchors and heads strait up the vertical face. Passing pockets and vertical edged features, the crux is behind you when you arrive at the upper dihedral. A bolted rap anchor requires a 70M rope or a 50M easily gets you back to the top of the first pitch. 9+, 65ftNote: Climbers, belayers and observers should wear a helmet at all times. Thank you for climbing safely and helping keep the routes clean of loose rocks.

name: Beehive
description: Nice long moderate climb. Mostly less than vertical, with a few steeper sections mixed in for some fun. At points you can choose left or right for a short section and depending which way you go it will vary the difficulty.

name: Grand Staircase
description: Last Climb: This is the first approach descent and the last climb of the day. Be sure to log your ascent of this classic last climb of the day! Repeat as needed! Thanks Bill for having the stairs built for all of us to enjoy.

name: Old Prospector
description: Bolted by Jim Thurmond, during the first year or so of Robinson’s development, as a great test piece for the stronger climbers visiting the area. The start of the route continues to grow longer, as a bouldering problem with a sit start in the cave. Enjoy the boulder problem or give it a go as a standing start from below the first bolt perma-draw.

name: Pillow Fort
description: This slightly overhanging route, located at the bottom of the steps, is just on the right side of the cave and extended another 15 ft, in May of 2018, to continue through the upper roof bulge. Permadraws protect the crux and last few bolts so go ahead and warm up on this line. An easy clip rap anchor allows for a quick, clean finish. I recommend this line for those of you wanting to warm-up for the harder lines at Robinson. Bouldering: Feel free to sit start, using the pockets. Crux: tends to be the mid section of the climb, at the third bolt. Be happy with the slopers then a fist jam helps you get past the large, horizontal pocket.

name: Project 2
description: NOTE: Route currently under construction but bound to be another classic!  This will be another perma-draw sport route just left of the center of the cave.

name: Project 3
description: NOTE: Route currently under construction but bound to be another classic!  This line will start on the far left side of the cave, following a steep face to a ledge above the cave, then continuing up the face above.

name: Project 4
description: NOTE: Route currently under construction but bound to be another classic!  This line will start in the lower dihedral formation, just right of Bee Hive.

name: Cryptic Choss
description: This is going to be a really nice route once it cleans up. It needs some traffic. You have a fairly high first bolt but an easy stairway on the right to get up to it.  After the 2nd bolt and then again at the top you need to pick left or right which will either make it easier or harder. Nice little hueco to stand in while you clip the anchors or clean. Make sure your belayer has a helmet.

name: Electric Skateboard
description: Climb to the left of the bolts on small positive holds and enjoy the crux near the finish.

name: Flash Mob
description: Flash Mob is bound to become a classic at Robinson. This left-facing dihedral starts as an easy stair step progression through 2nd class and 3rd class climbing to gain easy 5th class below the base of the beginning of the dihedral. Stay just left of the crack and follow the warm up holds to the next great rest. The inside corner (dihedral) features provide a layback stance, stemming moves, and perfect rest positions as you work your way up the climb. Just take your time, all of the holds are there.

name: Fragile Flake
description: A nice challenge for 11 climbers. Tends to stay wet for a while after a rain.

name: Magic Carpet Ride aka One for Bill
description: Bolted by Eric Lewis Gentle slab start pushes a bit more vertical but remains slab until a small bulge with bucket jugs at the top of the climb. Stay to the right of most of the bolts until you pass the half way point. Traverse slightly left to climb on the left hand side, continuing past two more bolts below the bulge.

name: Beer Ledge
description: Similar start to Tennessee Whisky, but head up and left from the first bolt, on the left side of the large stack of boulders. Crux is mid way up the route and greatly depends on if you are left or right of the bolt path. Finish on slightly easier climbing.

name: Bolts Gone Wild
description: This tall line involves a diversity of different features and climbing techniques. Quite a good find which didn't easily manifest into existence without a quite a bit of hard work and attention to detail by Norm Reed.  The slightly overhanging face starts with some easier climbing up through the grey rock section to an elongated pocket crack. Layback and look for a high step and then a smear, moving slightly up and left to gain the next rest position. The next 10 meters involves a face climbing sequence, moving up and slightly right then angling up and left towards a ledge at the base of the upper dihedral. The ledge is your next rest position.  The upper dihedral and face involves a bit of stemming then back to face climbing. To gain the top rap anchors, continue up right then straight up to the anchors.

name: Contrived
description: Left of the Party Boat crack, this line starts sharing holds with Show Boat then follows the slight arete straight up. Separate bolts protect this line. Separate rap anchors provided also. You can continue on the second pitch but I do not give it many stars until more cleaning has happened.

name: Delivery Service
description: Description coming soon, some cleaning required.

name: Exit Stage Left
description: Exit Stage Left is a steep slab line with a short section of creative side stepping to gain the upper section. Step up, smearing on the lower slab, then continue through a steeper section, moving left to exit the crux of the route. Continue up the rest of the steep slab to the top anchors.

name: Hi Holes
description: Start on steep face below large pockets. Crux is above pocket, moving through a thin face sequence. Mid-route rap anchors are convenient to lower off after the crux or reduce rope drag if climbing as a two pitch climb to the second set of rap anchors above the next ledge.

name: Legacy Falls
description: One of the first bolted lines on the Legacy Wall. Legacy was first free climbed by Isaiah Vuaght, out of St. Louis, MO, while he was visiting from school, in Columbia, MO. The route follows a steep line up a dark red face, with a continuous crux on the upper half of the climb.  Head up the easier lower portion of the line to reach the cave ledge. Large slotted pockets and a wide stance get you up and on the upper face. Climb roughly straight up and slightly left then up to the top anchors.  When it rains it pours down this line, hence the name of the route.

name: Mr. Turtle
description: Description on its way soon

name: Party Boat
description: Start on the fun lower slab then head up and into the left facing dihedral crack. This section can get pumpy depending on if you like crack climbing. The right hand side pulls on the other side of the column are fantastic. You'll also encounter an undercling that's a lifesaver.  The crux is moving through the crack and back onto the face. Rap anchors allow for easy quick draw retrieval.

name: Saturday Detention
description: If your going to be a Vandal you'll have to do Saturday Detention. 31m if fun. The fun starts right off the ground so make sure you're solid or stickclip the first bolt.    First Crux comes about 45' pulling through the small overhang. Footwork is everything here with little high stepping fun it should be no problem. The climbing is pretty consistent for the rating through the whole route

name: Show Boat "Horseshoe 8"
description: This dihedral is the first pitch of a two pitch route.  Easy 4th class climbing gets you up to the 1st bolt then jugs to the second. Now standing, in the base of the dihedral, easy 5th class (5.3 - 5.4) stemming gets you up to the two bolt anchor.

name: Skipper
description: Some continued cleaning needed below the second or third bolt and just below the rap anchors, otherwise this line is quite fun. Pockets and exciting movement makes for another good line at Robinson!

name: Tennessee Whisky
description: Head up left side of large stack of boulders to reach first anchor. Reach high to gain second anchor for the top of the rock stack. Small lower roof is below steep slab. Hueco holes start below the upper roof and angling crack, then continue in a sequential fashion, leading into the crux. Traverse a couple steps left to utilize the upper arete. Balance is key. Keep from becoming pumped by resting when possible. Quite a fun line!

name: Three Hour Tour
description: 3 Hour Tour is a two pitch line that follows the ridge path of least resistance. Pitch 1: Start on Party Boat crack, which is the money pitch, to the first set of belay anchors. Pitch 2: Then continue up and over bulges, moving slightly left with each ledge. Perma-draws provided for some of the bolts. Easy climbing traverses you left and up to the top anchors.  Rapping: Top rap anchors can make it a bit difficult to clean the line so perma-draw anchors are present to help redirect the rappel if some cleaning was not accomplished by the 2nd climber. Consider rope length and rap position when coming down. Rapping off the top anchors straight down puts you coming down from above Show Boat crack. If using a shorter rope, an optional rap station is half way down, on Show Boat. See Photo! Some cleaning still required as of spring of 2019.

name: Vandal
description: A good route with good movement. There is a short reachy crux section about halfway up just before you pull over a small lip to the "Thank God no hands rest ledge". First bolt is pretty high so if you're not solid in the grade bring a stick clip. Good exposure and a great view at the top.

name: 2 O'Clock Shadow
description: 60 meter or longer rope is required for this line. If you are climbing with a 50 meter rope, feel free to use the mid-route rap station. Route progressively gets harder as you climb, with the crux near the last few bolts. The darker red rock is usually a sign of water runoff and seasonal drainage so some minor dusting of holds may be required, from time-to-time. Line was bolted by Bill Weishaar using glue-in eye bolts, stainless rap chains and quick clip rap hooks. First ascent goes to Kelly Foster.

name: Abominable Flowman
description: Pull through some easy climbing until you get into the grey scoop in the wall. Pull up on some thin hold to some big moves. Climb over the small overhang to get to a good clipping jug. Get what rest you can here then push until you reach there no hands rest under a small overhang. Pull the overhang then enjoy a victory lap to the chains.

name: Alternate ending
description: In every choose your own adventure book there's a alternate end.  This is the alternate for Cave of Time.  Start is the same as Cave of Time. When you reach the roof you'll be faced with a choice,  the right path or the left.  If you choose the left, fix to the anchors on the left wall of the cave and bring up your second. Climb out of the cave to find your own path out of the Cave of Time.  Don't try to lead it as a single pitch as a fall above the roof would mean hitting the ledge below due to the amount of rope out. If you're not solid in the grade I suggest fixing to the first bolt of the second pitch to clip the second bolt then lower back into the cave for the start.  The first bolt is only there to prevent a factor 2 fall onto the anchor.

name: Blue Orchid
description: Flat gray slab to a bulge. Hanging slab to the flower petals on the overhanging orchid.

name: Bluff Banter
description: Bluff Banter moves a bit back and forth, from side to side, as the line works a path to the anchors below a large cedar tree. The climb starts easy and turns a bit more technical with the more vertical face above. Feel free to stay just right of the bolts or left for a different crux feel 3/4 of the way up the line. Climb past the last bolt for an easier, juggy finish. Rap chains provide an easy rappel.

name: Cave of Time
description: Starts just left of the first bolt climb 5.9 for the first four bolts then the business starts. Then 10 ft 5.10a to a good no hands rest to clip from. This is where the first Crux starts. Use a rail out left to get a high reach for a jug and then come back right to a good two hand pocket to clip from. Things let up after the next bolt until you reach the cave and get another great rest. (You could sit up there all day if so inclined.) Once you've rested enough start the second crux

name: Excalibur
description: A long climb with a few challenging sections and clean rock.  A 60 meter rope will work. After getting past the first bolt you have easier climbing and good stances to the 5th bolt where you run into the mid crux. Continue climbing towards the dihedral where the final crux moves are entering and exiting the dihedral.

name: Sawasdee
description: 60 meter or longer rope is required for this line. If you are climbing with a 50 meter rope, feel free to use the mid-route rap station during your descent or break up the climb and practice multi-pitch rope work. Route progressively gets harder as you climb, with the crux near the last few bolts. The darker red rock is usually a sign of water runoff and seasonal drainage so some minor dusting of holds may be required, from time-to-time. Stay on the right side of the red rock near the lighter white rock as you approach the upper crux. Line was bolted by Bill Weishaar using glue-in eye bolts, stainless rap chains and quick clip rap hooks.

name: Broken Arrow
description: Start with a couple moderate moves through the 4th bolt. You'll end up going right for a while, then coming back left, then right again.  Keep looking for the good holds, they may not always be straight up. Use a couple longer draws on bolts 5 and 6 to reduce rope drag through the ledge.   Then a good section of rock to the crux between the last bolt and the anchors.

name: Dream Catcher
description: Start with easy climbing to the first bolt. Stick clip recommended if not comfortable climbing 14 ft to first bolt.  Lots of good holds and stances to the top.

name: Scorpion
description: First bolt is 15 ft off the ground, with easy climbing.  The Crux is around the middle of the climb over the buldge. Then to easier climbing to the top. A couple Alpine draws will cut down on rope drag.

name: Tomahawk
description: Pitch 1: Start by navigate the lower bulge and crack between 2nd and 3rd bolts to gain easier climbing.  This section can be more difficult if the routes is not completely dry. The climb becomes more of a flat, slightly vertical face. Layback to the left at the 6th bolt and then move to the right a bit to reach the first set of chains. The crux is just below the chains and may require another layback off a right hand to clip with your left. Reach movements are required to utilize the bigger holds and avoid crimps. The last traverse right is challenging and involves some smearing and a high reach before clipping.  Pitch 1: Keep climbing another 40 feet with the crux involving moving up from the first set of rap anchors. Then through easy climbing terrain up to the finishing hooks at the top.

name: War Hammer
description: Use your stick clip since the start is tricky with limited feet. A series of good small ledges will take you to the 6th bolt, this is were the next crux is, after that  nice holds to the anchors located under small cedar tree.

name: The Watchtower
description: Obvious right facing dihedrals leading up from a great belay stance area to an obvious cedar tree at the anchors. 9 bolts but take plenty of extras so to be able to access from both sides when clipping. Crux is just after mid dihedral when moving right then up with a longer reach. The second crux is the section below the anchors but a good jug is present at the anchors.   Thank you Eric Lewis for cleaning this gem and constructing the wonderful staging area below the route!

name: Young Blood
description: The line gets increasingly more difficult the higher you climb. Jugs take you past the big flakes at the bottom and the first 4 bolts. Then the face turns a bit more vertical and balance is more important. holds decrease in size and the small pockets become important. It was a bit muddy during my last climb which made the climb feel harder like a 5.9 or so. (Still a new climb as of Jan 2020) The crux moves are just below the anchors. The last clip is fairly close to rap anchors so you are well protected for the move. The climb would be rated a bit harder if it was extended another 10 or 15 ft towards the upper lip.

name: Asylum
description: Belay from top tier, with belayer protection bolt. Climb past ledge to get to left part of roof. Crux is the first few moves through the left side of the roof. Stretch for the nice shelves to get past the bulge.  Small hands at top but still good holds and a god send left hand 2 finger pocket if you find it.  Really fun route.

name: Blitzkrieg
description: Belay from second tier or next to Wall.  1st bolt is on the main wall 10ft up from the ledge.  A little more shelf climbing than the typical Robinson pocket climbing makes it fun and interesting. The Crux is in the middle. Then easier climbing to the anchors.

name: Guerilla Warfare
description: Beautiful red/orange rock just right of the dihedral. Lots of fun, plenty of holds.  Try to stay balanced at the anchors.  Belay from top tier, with bolt for belayer or next to wall with another bolt for belayer. 1st bolt is ten foot up from ledge.

name: Guillotine
description: Belay from top tier with belayer bolt. Climb past ledge with roots, to first bolt. Longer draw will reduce rope drag on first bolt. Crux is in the middle of the climb going over the bulge. Fairly easy route staying left of the bolt line all the way to the anchors.

name: Ichabod
description: An easy, juggy start to the 4th bolt leads you up to the ten feet of crux. The use of wide stance stemming technique and you'll be home free. May feel a bit harder to a shorter climber.  * Note  - Route and trail improvements are currently underway so be aware of climbers cleaning along the trail and rock routes. Please be considerate to the developers/bolters.

name: Kamakazi
description: Belay from first tier, route is furthest right on South facing wall.  1st bolt is eight ft from the ground. Climb past easy ledge to the main wall.  The Crux is at the top of the climb.

name: Lost Souls
description: Starting moves are difficult, then easier climbing to middle of climb where the two small Crux sections are . Finishing going right to anchors.  Good hands most of the climb.

name: C Is For Crumpecker
description: Need a bail bond or some used auto parts? See Mr. C in nearby Tiff, Missouri!  Otherwise, try this route. It starts by the beautiful left leaning crack that ends much too soon....

name: Here's To You, Mrs. Robinson
description: This route begins in a right facing dihedral and a high first clip. It is between the routes "TGIF", on the left, and “My Covid 19 Shelter” on the right. After the third bolt the route bears slightly right, ignoring TGIF, which is close by on the left. With the movie in mind, you just may feel like shouting "ELAINE!" when you reach the clip-in anchors.

name: My Covid-19 Shelter
description: This route maintains a safe social distance from Mrs. Robinson on the left and Crumpecker on the right. Climb straight up to the massive orange hooks. The hardest moves occur in two places - near the start and later in the steep area above the first ledge.

name: Oh Stormy
description: This short route is on the left end of the Landing. It starts between “Illegal smile” on the left and “Tiny Hands” farther right. It is pumpy and fun. You'll be glad there's a bomber left side pull at you're getting through the crux.  The climber may experience feelings of intense physical pleasure upon reaching its summit.

name: Quarantine Thyself
description: This long route starts about 6 feet to the right of Crumpecker and stays just left of two large trees.The first tree is clutching the rock 15 feet up and looms over the first crux. The second tree is near the top and provides shade for the second crux,  a right facing headwall. There is an eyebolt in this second tree which may help keep your rope out of the dirt  and gravel at the base of the headwall....

name: Robinson Crusoe
description: This route is named after an early pioneer in social distancing. His story was published 300 years ago!  The route starts on the left side of an arete. Mrs Robinson is around the corner on the right.  As usual, the hardest part is near the bottom

name: TGIF
description: The title refers to Robinson Crusoe's companion, Friday. The route goes up the arete and, at times, seems somewhat squeezed between Crusoe and Mrs. Robinson.  The crux is a couple bolts up where you have to get over the bulge and you're looking for hands.  A little more difficult if you're short.

name: Tiny Hands
description: This left leaning route is near the left end of The Landing. Unlike the other routes, the crux here is near the top. The route has some good holds which are small. So if your hands are tiny you might like it - unless, of course , you are over 70 years old and weigh over 240. In that case, better stick to golf and tweeting.There is an interesting variation to this route worth trying on top rope (using the Tiny Hands anchor). Just left of the start up the first three bolts is a dihedral which is quite challenging.

name: Angel From Montgomery
description: “ How the hell can a person go to work in the morning and come home in the evening and have nothing to say?” There are two ways to start this route. The easier way is from the right following the left leaning bolt line. The harder is going straight up to the second bolt. The crux involves getting past the third bolt.

name: Dear Abby
description: Dear Abby is the left-most route on the John Prine wall.  It is right by the big White Oak tree. The big white oak tree has numerous scars from all the rocks that have recently bounced off it on their way to the river.

name: Fish and Whistle
description: "Father forgive us for what we must do, You forgive us and we'll forgive you. We'll forgive each other 'til we both turn blue, and go whistle and fishing in the heavens."This route has perhaps the easiest start on the wall, but it becomes delicate and interesting up on the ledge.

name: Illegal Smile
description: “ I chased a rainbow down a street — dead end. And all my friends turned out to be — insurance salesman.” This route starts just right of “We are the lonely”. It then goes up the right side of a steep arete.

name: Leave The Lights On
description: "It's like sitting in the kitchen when the music's really bitchin' Your nose it starts to itchin' As you count your old age pension ... Got a big ol' dog, a chrome crowbar I keep that mother humper in the back seat of my car."This route is something of a one move wonder - well, maybe two. It has an easy start and an easy finish. The crux is getting past the third bolt where the holds are small and far apart. Tall folks may find it easy but short people will have a battle on their hands.

name: Let's Talk Dirty In Hawaiian
description: “...waka waka nuka licka, would you like a lei? Eh?” This is the longest route on the JP wall. It’s about 6 feet right of Sam Stone.

name: Sam Stone
description: ”There’s a hole in Daddy’s arm where all the money goes”.  This route is right of Dear Abby and even closer to the big Oak Tree. The tree is on for those who find the start difficult. There is a nice layback section provided by the flake above the third bolt.

name: We Are The Lonely
description: “Worthless, ruthless, toothless man wants wealthy women with a plan.” This route is at the North end of the JP wall, next to the sign for the wall and a large tree.Near the fifth bolt, move right to better holds

name: C is for Cookie
description: On the far left hand side of the City Limit Wall, start below the C-shaped, shallow dihedral, then follow it up to a small roof to find the crux. Once you have clipped the rap anchors, you have passed the hard part so enjoy the view of the river and remember to thank your belayer.

name: Project 5.11
description: NOTE: Route currently under construction but bound to be another classic!  Warning: Route off limits during construction. Some cleaning required. Bolted by Marcus Floyd

name: Project 5.9
description: NOTE: This route is currently under construction.  Warning: Some cleaning required.  Route is found in the center of the City Limit Wall and starts below a small roof. Traverse up and slightly right to gain a rest stance at the base of the open, right-facing dihedral. Follow the feature up.

name: Begin Again
description: Scramble up the start, to below the first bolt.  A consistently technical route with periodic rests. In the top half you wish for more feet for a few moves.  Also staying in the bolt line at the top, can make it harder. Stay left of the bolt line for an easier time through the crux section. Lots of fun.  Perma-draws at the top.

name: Blue Tail Rising
description: Thanks to Norm Reed, this wonderful line heads out the left side of the Grotto Wall's main roof. Permadraws provided through the roof crux section. P1: Start by following a dihedral feature up the lower face. Head slight left, at the roof, then straight up through several power demanding pulls to reach the set of rap anchors. 10+, 75ft  P2: Continue following a line of bolts up easier slab to reach the second set of rap anchors at the top of the pillar. 5.5, 40ft 70M rope required or double rope rap off the top of the second pitch.

name: Corrie's Kazoo
description: A funky challenge with a tough belay area.

name: Fight or Flight
description: 70 meter rope recommended, if you're doing both pitches at once, otherwise a 60M works great. P1: Bouldery crux start pushes past the lower small roof to a small ledge. Stem past the next several bolts to gain the slab under the obvious, main roof. You will feel the roof crux immediately when it forces several reaches and sustained movement. A section of vertical face leads to the first pitch rap anchors. 10d, 80ft P2: Past the first rap anchors, the climbing terrain turns to easier slab and follows a handful of bolts to a second set of rap anchors, towards the top of the pillar. Requires a 70M rope or double rope rap from this point of the climb. 5.5, 35ft

name: Road to Mordor
description: Arching crack that traverses left below the obvious roof above. Start right with a short, standing start, V1- boulder problem then it lets up to some easy 5.7 climbing once you're over the lip. Then head up to the roof and follow it left. You can finish by lowering off on the fixed gear or get a workout on the top half of Blue Tail Rising. A really fun route with movement you don't see everyday.  If you go for the link up make sure to bring a 70m rope.

name: Shelob's Lair
description: Start on the same start as Road to Mordor. This start sequence is the crux of the climb. Instead of traversing left under the roof, continue straight up and right on the face above.  You might think your next crux would be at the baby roof, mid way up the climb, where you go straight instead of left following RTM, but that move isn't too bad.  Up a little higher, you have to look around more for feet, but they're there. This line is well protected!

name: Big River 2 Step
description: Start in the dihedral and stem through the 5.8 moves to get past the first two bolts then to the ledge. Clip the ledge bolt then above the ledge go up staying right of the next two bolts and baby dihedral to make it a little easier (5.7), or go straight up the bolt line if you'd like to experience the 5.9 moves. From there it's a cruise to the top.  A 60 meter rope will barely get you down if you include rope stretch. Better to use a 70, but either way tie safety knots and wear a helmet.

name: Alpine
description: Well what can you say. It's short, easy, and a good warm up if you need one, and shares anchors with Golden Ticket #1, just to the right. Head past the the first few bolts by angling up and right, then clip a bolt to your right before finishing at the rap anchors.

name: Britton
description: If you're short might be a good idea to stick clip the 2nd bolt.  The bottom is all pretty easy.  Getting to the anchors after clipping the last bolt might be the crux.

name: Fingland The Finger Lock
description: This route is a bit of a conundrum. You might think you're at HCR.  It's a pretty difficult V4 boulder move to get off the ground, but once you're at the 2nd bolt turns into a nice 5.9 with sidepulls, some stemming and nice ledge for a rest before going for the last 15 feet. If you're tall the start might be considerably easier.  Shares anchors with Funky Side Pulls.

name: Funky Side Pulls
description: Get yourself started and then remember the name of the route for beta.

name: Golden Ticket  1
description: A little trickier than it looks, but still a fun little route. Start below the first bolt, right of the route Alpine, and continue straight up to avoid skirting left. Shares anchors with Alpine.

name: Gusher
description: A bouldery crux is below the first bolt. Feel free to use a stick clip then follow the line of tan bolts through the line of pockets, up an open dihedral, just left of Red Dihedral. The second crux is near the top. Keep a wide stance and climb with confidence. Route gets its name from when I was bolting the line. Midway up, while drilling an anchor hole, the drill bit penetrated a pocket of rock that was holding about five gallons of water. Immediately, water squirted from around the drill bit and started gushing out of the hole in the rock, like an oil well. Hence the name. A different hole was then drilled for the bolt.

name: Holes In The Ceiling
description: Sweet route directly to the right of the Red Dihedral. Standing at the bottom you can see what looks to be holes 3/4s the way up. The Crux is moving through those holes and making a throw off the last one.

name: Horses Mouth
description: A steep slab crux leads to a small ledge rest then up a short dihedral at the top. Two permadraws allows you to work the tricky upper section without the fear of needing to leave your gear. Climb with confidence. Use the big pocket underclings (horse like mouth) to  work your feet up. Reach out left to use laybacks to gain the raps anchors above. Route feed back has included the feeling that the line feels a bit more like a 10 b/c.

name: Jon Without A "H"
description: Another route where the challenge is getting started.

name: Red Dihedral
description: One of the first "great" routes at RB. The crux is getting to the 2nd bolt. From there it's just a fun ride to the top. Stick clipping the 2nd bolt is a good idea.

name: S&M
description: Two routes left of Sweet Crack, follow vertical edges past a steep crux section between bolts 2 and 3, below the small ledge. Then the middle is a fun little ride.  The second crux is near the top on the vertical face with horizontal holds. S & M stands for Steve and Marcus. Steve Martin cleaned the line, which was no small order, then placed the rap anchors so the route could be easily top roped. Thanks for your hard work Steve!

name: Sweet Crack
description: Stem and jam up the finger crack and corner to a ledge, then pull an airy move over the bulge and make your way up to the anchor.

name: Unclung Hero
description: Well the bottom is easy and the middle is fun. Then you get to the top.

name: Ain't No Thing But A Chicken Wing
description: Gain the small shelf about 3-4 ft up and navigate through the rather thin but fun lower 1/3 of the route. The rest is quite easy as you get to the top and share the last bolt and anchors with Tito's Arete.

name: Blue Nude
description: Climb through technical crimps and pockets up to a committing crux.  High feet, a good plan, and a jug make a tough move to a sharp easy finish. The crux might be height dependent.

name: Combo Number 5
description: A route that looks easier than it is. The bottom is delicate, it's easier if you go right, but then if you're leading it's hard to reach your clips.  The middle is fun but then the top is the 10a/b portion with the baby roof and limited good holds.

name: Crescendo
description: Beta courtesy of Matt D.   Up to just below the 4th bolt it's fairly straight forward, you can skip a couple holds and there's some fairly sharp pockets along the way. This section goes at about 11b.  At bolt 4 the crux kicks in as you're holding a poor left hand and trying to continue bumping the right hand up on side pulls. After bolt 5 look for a left hand side pull as you follow a crimp line with the right hand.  Nice left hand jug at the anchors.  Thanks Matt!

name: Crimson Wonder
description: A steep start leads into easy climbing straight up the bolt line.  Obvious crux at the permadraws.  Find the good holds for a short boulder sequence to finish at the anchors.

name: Dirty Taco
description: We're updating route info as quickly as possible, please be patient.

name: Drifter
description: Start route following tan bolt hangers and continue straight up using side pulls after the generous pocket below the second bolt. This starts just left of the 5.12 and is two climbs right of Number One.  Perma draws allow for confident climbs without the worry of loosing gear. Chain are at the top but you can lower from the perma draws. Stick clipping the first or second bolt is possible with a longer pole.

name: Duel Administration
description: This really fun climb goes up juggy pockets until around the fourth bolt. The crux section goes from bolts 5-7. Move up and a little right from the fifth bolt and either clip #6 high off some crimps or go up higher to a fairly good two-hand rail and clip from there. Going from 6 to 7 is a bit easier using some good but very rough and painful pockets and up to some jugs by the 7th bolt. Smooth sailing once you've got that one locked down.

name: Imagined Landscapes
description: This route is mostly a jug haul over a series of small ledges, with the crux about half way up. Check out some of the cool (geodes?) shining inside many of the pockets.

name: Le Reve
description: Le Reve starts just right of the bench like boulder at the base of the Picasso Wall. With a little good footwork pull on some small holds to a bomber ledge to clip the first bolt. Then work the slab pockets for some easy climbing to get to second bolt. From here on it's all fixed draws(bring a third if you plan on setting a top-rope).     The first crux is the sequence through the vertical borehole like pocket with the undercling at the top.  The second crux comes right after. Throw high for a three finger pocket, get higher feet and pull hard to a crimp just above the crack in right of the upside-down triangle feature. Pull the overhang to be rewarded with a good right side-pull and small edges to the the top.

name: Number 1
description: A route that looks a little easier than it is. As you traverse right in the middle you find your self looking for holds. The last bolt is left of the anchors, clip it and then traverse right.  If you go straight up you make it a more difficult finish.

name: Puttin' On The Ritz
description: Technical work early on leads to a cushy life up top.

name: Redtail
description: Redtail starts as a 5.2 - 5.3 slab that gets serious when it turns vertical below the obvious Picasso roof. At the alcove, stay right and use small edges to gain the pockets. Climb very intentionally, for the pockets are positive but some are positively sharp! Once you reach the large pocket at the roof, the crux subsides if you keep working the feet gracefully.

name: Thunder Dome
description: Steep face to the right of Duel Administration leads up to a roof bulge and a left hand under cling.  From the under cling it's a long right hand reach to a crimp which is the start of the crux.  Once you are over the roof bulge a couple of balancing moves takes you to the anchors.

name: Titos Arete
description: Nice technical arete climbing gets you up to a ledge, then a bit less difficult arete/face climbing takes you to the anchors. Shares anchors with Ain't No Thing But A Chicken Wing.

name: Free Cholo
description: We are in the process of bolting this route - it's not available to climb yet.  This line starts on a vertical face right of Ray's Cow Bell. The route gets less steep the higher you climb but offers a great layback on a left facing flake feature. the crux of the route is in the lower to mid portion of the climb. Rap anchors allow for an easy lower when finished.

name: Giverny
description: A tricky little route that requires some thought for a 5.9.  Take it slowly, decide whether to follow the bolt line (harder) or stay to the side and enjoy the trip to the top.

name: Homemade Hatchet
description: The bottom is super easy 5.4, but once you get up to the upper face, you'll need to clip a bolt, with a chain that extends the clipping range over the edge.  Clipping this bolt was part of the crux. Climbing up over the bulge can be elusively frustrating if you do not find the right hold. Grab a good right hand layback and mantle with the left. Avoid using the tree if it still remains.

name: Ray's Cow Bell
description: Another of the long routes at Robinson.  Pretty easy as you go with what challenge there is coming in the last 10-15 feet.

name: Sacre Bleu
description: A really enjoyable climb, that's pretty much a cruise. Stay right of the bolt line the whole way, particularly after the 3rd bolt where looking left will show you nothing but a blank wall. A nice shelf for a rest before you take care of the last 2 bolts.

name: Salvador's Dolly
description: Easy climb with one balance move when you're clipping.  A couple great rests as you go and a nice stance for clipping/cleaning the anchors.

name: Can U Hear Me Now
description: A great route to practice your multi pitch skills.  1st set of anchors on a nice ledge about 20 ft up. Traverse up and to the right while grabbing some very nice pockets. You'll end up to the right of the bolt right before the ledge so lean left and clip that.  If you find the holds the top is also a lot of fun. This route has cleaned up nicely and since the first pitch is only 20 feet it's a great place to practice your multi-pitch skills.  If you want to stop at the ledge anchors I would call the bottom a 5.6.

name: How I Sent My Summer Vacation
description: Start under a baby roof and either go straight up where your feet are the challenge but your hands are good, or stay a little bit right with better feet but less great hands.  There is a gorgeous side pull down low if you find it.  Once you're at the 2nd bolt the route just becomes a cruise.

name: Norminator
description: A straight up route that doesn't wander on you. If the bottom is wet you can still make the start by staying left.  Great hands and feet for the first 3/4 of the route.  You'll be thinking it's an 8. Then the top is the 9+ part as it gets just a touch negative and you wish for more feet. Super nice, great re-climb value.

name: Gummy Bear
description: Good beginner route. Climb up the 2 platforms to a bowling ball hold move at the chains.

name: Milky Way
description: Climb flat face to overhang for difficult finish.

name: Of Coral and Kiwis
description: Route Information:Gain the obvious lower ledge, after the first bolt, using a couple smears and then climb up the inside corner jugs to a steeper section before the ledge at the chains. Rap down to prevent rope wear. If lowering, keep the rope in the obvious rock groove.

name: Pop Rocks
description: Climb up to the overhang, enjoy some laybacks and small finger pockets to the chains.

name: Rock Candy
description: Climb nice pockets to the crimpy bulge, pull over and finish with slightly easier climbing.

name: That's A Giggle
description: If you have a long enough stick clip you can literally clip the 3rd bolt before you jump on. Once you've pulled the baby roof and you're past the 2nd bolt, and have your feet up you're through the crux. Great shelf for practicing your cleaning skills. Your main challenge is finding the right pockets while going through the crux before the pump sets in.

name: Tootsie Pops
description: Stem up the dihedral to the chains. Another nice short warm up route.

name: Twizzler
description: Easy climbing will take you through to the second bolt.  Take advantage of a good, quick rest (if you desire) while you prepare to take on the crux through bolts three and four.  Underclings exist for clipping both.   Get through some technical climbing through the crux to find another good undercling rest on bolt four.  Shake out and continue onto much easier terrain to the anchor.

name: Buffalo Trace
description: Just a little bit trickier at the bottom than Hot Toddy so you need to figure out how to get up past the 3rd bolt.  From there it's a cruise to the top.

name: Hot Toddy
description: The start is a little baby boulder move so boulder on up to the shelf or stick clip.  From there it's pretty simple with a nice dihedral move at the top.  Bolted by Dan Rapp.

name: Braille Arete
description: This sit start follows a sequence of pockets vertically along The Den's rounded arete. Sequence is important for following the easiest path to the top. If it feels harder, try to rework the handhold sequence. The holds get bigger the higher you climb. Jug finished allows you to stand on the top.

name: Dan's JUGS
description: Pocket jugs in the corner of The Den still needs some cleaning but has the potential for being another great warm-up.

name: Grotto Birth
description: Start all the way back in the small cave.  This start involves, beginning as far back as possible, keeping your feet off the ground, pressed against the side walls and hands pressed for confined stemming. (V0)  Now, just inside the cave opening, the line moves out and straight up to the top, following a line of jugs. (V0-) Suggest a spotter for this one, some rocks litter the landing area. Also, one of the jugs inside the cave is thin so use the better part of the hold for a secure undercling.

name: Juggernaut
description: Lower crux leads to jugs for a finish top-out.

name: Mini Spire
description: Climb the front section of taller, clean rock and step off of the short backside of the Mini Spire.

name: One Way Out of This
description: Climb starts as a sit start, just inside the cave opening, then the line moves out and left then straight up to the top, following a line of jugs. Suggest a spotter for this one, some rocks litter the landing area. Also, one of the jugs inside the cave is thin so use the better part of the hold for a secure undercling.  A second start option involves beginning as far back as possible, keeping your feet off the ground and pressed against the side walls and hands pressed for confined stemming. Continue out following the basic sit start option. (V0-)

name: Seam of Dreams
description: Crux is just a few moves in then easier climbing to top it out.

name: Crisscross
description: Start with hands on the lip of the roof and use a right heel hook to gain higher hands. Transition from right heel to right toe smear to bump your right hand to high hold. Difficulty is now over. Stand up and finish the short slab and traverse left to the tree slab down climb.

name: Easy Ramp
description: The obvious corner ramp on the right side of the Wave Roof, just after the roof ends. Useful for scoping out the higher holds on Sencha Boost. Downclimb until the shrubs up top (possibly poison ivy?) are cleared or you can traverse left at a harder grade (V0) at the top on awesome holds to join the top of Sencha Boost.

name: Mono y Mono
description: On the left side of the Wave Roof, just right of the big tree, start from a sit start and reach out to holds along the lip. Pull the lip to continue up the slab to the top of the exposed rock. I recommend down climbing by stepping left to easier rock, avoiding any dirt and plants above.   Great landing area but can hold a bit of moisture during the wet season. Take a tarp folded inside your bouldering pad. See photos

name: Sencha Boost
description: From a sit start beneath the roof, reach out then pull through the roof. Then up on fun pockets and ledges until you can make the exciting reach to a good jug just over the lip. From there, smear and throw for the amazing jug a bit farther back. Top out and walk off to the right. A bit committing up high but it's easy to stick a leg behind you and escape via Easy Ramp.

name: Standing Cross
description: This is the standing start option for one of the center roof lines. Reach high and grab a good left hand and reach far right to get a lower right hand. Use a high right foot, at the lip of the roof to then bump your right hand up to a high right hold. After reaching the top of the slab, avoid the dirt walk around by traversing left on good feet to reach the down climb tree slab.

name: Tree Side Down Climb
description: Left side of the Wave Wall is the easy down climb and an easy boulder problem for those looking to scuff up those new shoes!

name: No. 10
description: Crack. Starts narrow and widens towards the top

name: No. 11
description: Start in the horizontal crack high up, then use the two parallel hand cracks.

name: No. 8
description: Hand crack

name: No. 9
description: Hand crack

name: No. 54
description: Arete

name: No. 55
description: Use combination of jams, laybacks, and face holds to ascend the vertical crack

name: No. 56
description: Sit start, work left in the diagonal crack to a block then go up the face using small holds.

name: No. 57
description: Lieback a thin vertical edge to horizontal seams then top out.

name: No. 58
description: Use thin holds and a few well placed jugs to ascend right edge of the wall.

name: No. 35
description: Crack on the left side. Sit start

name: No. 36
description: Straight up through the vertical seam. Sit start

name: No. 37
description: Right arete. Sit start
Diagonal crack in the middle of the wall.  Use face holds to the right and crack.

name: Crystalline Crack (aka No. 71)
description: Friendly crack

name: Jim's (aka No. 67)
description: Great sustained splitter crack

name: Joe's (aka No. 68)
description: Great sustained splitter crack

name: School of Rock (aka No. 70)
description: Another great sustained splitter crack

name: Thad's (aka No. 75)
description: Follow the diagonal crack. Pulling the roof is the crux

name: True Grit (aka No. 69)
description: Follow the overhung corner and pull the moves through the face

Direct start with face holds or mantle up on left. Gain entry into the crack placing a piece low to prevent falling into the stream. Fingers to jams up at the top. This route was extremely dirty. Be sure to bring a nut tool or brush to clean out the crack.
Mantle up and gain a crack in a chimney/dihedreal. Stem and chimney your way up and pull through a small roof to top out.

name: Arc
description: Slab overlooking the river. Start low off the triangular rock in front of the face, move up and right on interesting holds and balancey compression. Spooky top out.

name: The Diamond
description: Thin crack

name: Naked Edge
description: Thin, spectacular crack system

name: Arch Crack (aka No. 108)
description: Follow the crack up to the roof, pull the short move, follow the arch up and left to top out.

name: Silver Miner (aka. No. 54)
description: Starting from the right edge of the Eagle's head roof, follow the finger crack

name: Hammer Head (aka No. 11)
description: Great crack climb with a nice finish

name: Hand Crack (aka No. 7)
description: Climb the face to finally place a good cam in a horizontal crack. Climb the crack to the top and build an anchor

name: Washed Away (aka No. 21)
description: Step out over the water and traverse right. Climb under the roof and use the crack to pull out over the roof and up the face.     A great route for the confident leader!

name: The Commandments Stone (aka No. 99)
description: Climb the big crack formed between the huge stone slab and the massive boulder. Follow the crack up underneath the roof, and exit to the right.

name: Fist Full Of Granite (aka No. 101)
description: Climb the perfect hand crack placing gear when necessary. Build and anchor at the top.

name: The Pickaxe (aka No. 102)
description: Traverse the rightward leaning crack to finish on Rock Candy. Build and anchor on Rock Candy.

name: Rock Candy (aka No. 103)
description: Climb the perfect hand crack placing gear when necessary

name: Beguile
description: Start on edges and use pockets to reach good jugs. From here pul up and stand on jugs. Follow the bolts to the top.

name: Fat boy strikes back
description: The crux is the start of the route then smear and stem your way to the top in the small dihedral.

name: H. R. T. C.
description: The low angle sport route on the left side of the gully. Climb the short face to gain a small ledge. Use great jugs as you lead up and into the upper face to eventually clip the anchor.

name: Recovery
description: Pull on good holds through the short section of hanging block limestone. Work your way onto the face and use pockets and edges to make your way to the top

name: Chockstone
description: Climb the crack using the chockstone until you reach a ledge. Clip the bolt and angle rightward to the top.

name: Little Trad
description: Moderate for St. Francious. Climb the mixed line top out straight and right. Strong contender for best route at the site.

name: Little Trad Direct
description: Beginning on Rendezvous, climb through the first two bolts, then angle up and left, through the dihedral, to a pair of safety anchors

name: Onlooker
description: Use small holds and get to a great pocket. Throw left and catch a good hold. Cross over right and work into good jug. Pull through one more tricky section and use good holds to reach the anchor.

name: Traditional Invisibility
description: Jam and ly-back your way to the top while placing gear as necessary. 2 safety anchors at the top.

name: Tre France'
description: Begin on a small hollowish flake launching up to a positive left hand crimp. From here utilize sidepulls and small crimps with a dash of some fancy footwork. Gain a great rest around the 4th bolt then bring it home. Wonderful route in a pretty cool setting.

name: Guide Crack
description: Climb the crack using face holds when possible to eventually reach the anchor

name: Heavy Bells
description: Climb through the wide section using good holds on the wall, eventually work into a layback. Protect the crack and climb to the apex of the crack. From here, climb the face and clip the anchor.

name: Hidden Corners
description: Climb the crack finding face holds along the way eventually reaching the anchors

name: Hittin the Vein
description: Utilize edges and sidepulls to eventually access the better hold on top.

name: Ottomania
description: Begin on the left inside corner, traverse up and right around the arete. Gain the face and proceed through thin holds till you gain back the arete up top.

name: Punching In A Dream
description: "Stick Clip The First Bolt"    Pull on small pockets until you reach a large block jug, from here work your way up to horizontal ledge, followed by traversing left and angling up towards bolted anchor

name: Way 13a
description: Open project for anyone up to a challenge

name: Wayward Traveler
description: Pull some hard moves and work towards laying back the crack. Follow the crack and eventually pull the slabby face to the anchors.

name: Pump Me Up
description: A fun little introduction to St. Francois climbing.  The crux is in the first ten feet of the route. Begin with some fun balancy moves, eventually gaining good holds.  Once you're past the third bolt, cruise to the anchor and you're home free!

name: Ripped Flesh
description: As with the other routes in this area, the first fifteen feet are the crux.  The holds are incredibly small crimps with tiny nubbins for feet.  Overall, though, beautiful moves to an easy finish!   **Note, I have no original beta on these routes, so I have chosen not to make up a name for something I was not the first to climb!***

name: Rubens Range
description: The classic traditional route of the park. Excellent route with high quality rock.  Layback the thin dihedral to a huge chockstone-like double-dihedral. From here, the choice is yours!  Use 'em both or pick a side.

name: Torn Tips
description: Follow the bolts using side pulls as you pull your way up the ramp.

name: Through the cracks
description: start in a pocket side pull on arete, use slot features work around arete on sharp crimps, move left to shelf, and up and right to finish.

name: Unkknown
description: Thin crimps on a steep vertical section of the east side or the boulder that faces the Slab Wall section of the Main Bluff. Top rope recommended!

name: The May Exhibit
description: Start low and left on apposing side pulls and follow obvious features up and right. Crux is a bit of a puzzle and probably will be different for everyone. Let me know if this has been done before if you have the info.

name: 1. Brain Drain
description: Standing start on good holds

name: 2. Long Traverse
description: Sit start low on the crocodile's mouth and traverse left tops our the same as Brain Drain.

name: 3. Cross-eyed
description: Sit start far right in the crack in the nose traverse left top out using the finger crack in the middle of the boulder.

name: 4. Digging For Gold
description: Sit start with matched hands on the nose crack. Top out using the pockets just to the left.

name: Captain Obvious
description: Captain Obvious is a standing start moves straight up and tops out tears the back of the boulder.

name: Cracking On
