description: Sit start with a funky pull on. Head up using the crack feature on the right. Gets a little burly at the top. The sit start is easy V3-ish, the stand start is something like V2 depending on wingspan. 2.5 stars if I could give it; it's a bit short for a full 3.

name: Hug Bug
description: Short but nice. Sit start matched on the corner, move up and left, and use some high feet to top out. With a few exceptions, the holds are unusually rounded for the area, and very solid.

name: My face is to pretty for slab
description: Easy standing start followed by a balancey middle to a satisfying top out

name: Unknown
description: The left arete of the steeper slab face on the Nubbin. Climb up from as low as you can on decent features just past the corner.

name: Jason Bourne's Butthole
description: It's start is under the roof pulling on the two finger pockets. Then you throw to the ledge outside the roof. Heal hook and pull up to the mono. Then mantle of the shelf to get the higher hold

name: Ultimatum
description: Sit start with two good jug pockets on either side of the corner. Make a medium-big move for a left crimp, slap up to good holds right. Move right around the corner to another jug pocket or follow the corner left a little further for a slightly tougher top.

name: Anybody Want a Peanut?
description: Saw some chalk so I figured why not. Good for warming up. Avoid the ledge for more fun.

name: Inconceivable
description: awesome problem. techy moves down low, come around the roof big move up, and commiting moves at the top.

name: Morla: The Ancient One
description: This is a simple solid V2 with a cool undercling start. Yellow= hand holds, blue=foot holds To start: match on bottom lip with left foot on bottom foot hold and high right toe hook behind the right jaw. Work hands across bottom lip, match right hand to right toe, big left slap to the slopey snoot with right foot on right most foot hold. To top big juggy hole at the top of the head and a high left head on left side of the mouth.  An extra jug just left of the big sharp crack and a sharp crimp above that

name: Prepare to Die
description: Start on your choice of two lower ledges, make your way up to a crimp rail, and then throw for the top.

name: R.O.U.Ss
description: R.O.U.Ss is easy dispatched with a little fire and perseverance. Standing start on small side clings so you can gain the ledge. Then throw big to the top of the overhang. Then with a little high foot action pull over the top.

name: Left side flake
description: Sit start, use the angled flake, top out left side of boulder

name: Up the middle
description: Sit to start with hands on the side cling and small pocket. Top out center of the Boulder.

name: All That Glitters
description: Start on the low obvious jug. Big move to a side pull match on top up to a slopey ledge. Holds at the lip and finish. Cool movement on solid rock.

name: Bedazzled
description: Sit start in the low slot move up the face using low side pulls and slopey pinches to a dynamic move to a crimp and slot before the jugs at the top.

name: eliminati
description: Pick your start one: same as just a little lie but go big and right to the tiny crimp then straight up. two: direct start(not as reachy) matched on a weird blocky feature to the tiny crimp then straight up. Nothing spectacular but a fun couple moves to add to your circuit.

name: Gary
description: Sit start, move up and right through big dumb moves on big dumb-ish holds (and one or two small ones). Could be a bit harder for shorter climbers.

name: Glitter Bomb
description: Start right hand on a undercling pocket left hand on arete. Work your way left up the arete. and the end of the short arete follow jugs to the top. Super low ball ridiculous start. Careful not to blow the first move and throw yourself of the ledge.

name: Just a Little Lie
description: Sit start with matched hands on the slightly mossy jug. Then lay back the arete until you can get the good holds up top.

name: Mud Crack
description: Start with a low sit using your right hand to grab a lip at head level and the left with a jam in the crack. Traverse up the crack and throw for the pocket halfway past the horizontal crack.

name: Shimmer
description: Sit start with paired underclings. Move up and out from under the roof with beta trickery and some big moves. The rock is a little prickly.

name: Cry me a river(left)
description: awkward foot above your head start super fun though!

name: Cry me a river(right)
description: Start on a scooped jug and heel hook, slap your way right using a rail, work up the short vertical section

name: Cry No More
description: This climb was hiding on the back side of the main boulder, between a few boulders. The difficulty of the climb varies from a standing or squatting position. Standing start with slopers is a V0 and a squatting position is around a V3-4. Crynomas is from a sitting position, from a bouldering pad, and is around a V6.

name: Crynomas
description: This is a hard sit start with very little for the feet.  If you'd like to take the edge off you can stand start which is V0. Maybe v3-4 for a shorter individual who can't reach the upper holds.

name: Low Down Dirty Shame
description: Standing start using the horizontal crack for your feet.

name: Vino Swinger
description: This line follows up through the scoop dished-out shape and starts from a standing start. A vine hangs nearby.

name: Popplers
description: sit start on jugs move up and slightly right the crux is the top out.

name: The Robot Devil
description: left hand big pocket, right hand small shallow slot, work over the bulge using hidden holds, gain the mediocre lip hold with a sweet spot, high feet, and rock over.

name: Robot Nixon
description: sit start matched on pocket side pull feature, small intermediate crimps or go big to the lip, use shallow holds over lip, and get up!

name: Scruffy, The Janitor
description: sit start on jugs move up on big holds and cool lay back feature.

name: The Year 252525
description: start on sharp jugs head sharp right work into water runnel feature straight up to the mantely finish.

name: Canary
description: A nice problem with great movement.  Sit start with your right hand hueco pocket and your left on the thin hold in the corner. The move up to the good holds on the outside of the roof.  Hey high feet and go for three spicy top-out.

name: How Now Brown Cow
description: Sit start with your hands under the cows head feature.  Then pull hard and throw for the top.

name: Mocking Bird
description: Variation of Song Bird. Sit start to the right of Song Bird about 5 feet. Starts with left hand in sharp 3 finger pocket, right hand pinch the small arete, and right leg knee-skums around the corner. Avoid using the shelves underneath for your left foot (sort of an eliminate). A hard opening sequence links you into the second half of Song Bird.

name: Quetzalcoatl
description: Variation of Canary couple more moves bigger holds same epic finish.

name: Song Bird
description: This is the direct line climbing out from the from the cave. Start with your left hand in the hueco pocket as your right on the crimp. Climb out using the pockets and underclings until you can pull the roof.  It's currently an open project so make sure to let me know if you get it.

name: [Redacted]
description: Just like the short bus this problem is made for the little people. Stand start with your hands in the vertical crack and right foot on the generous for chip to the right. Gaston and bump the left then get a high foot onto the right start hold for Skoolyard Bully. Before you know it you'll be home free.  There's an optional sit start which is V3/V4 start sitting with your left hand on the crimp just left of the of the crack and your right on the miniscule ledge low in the crack.

name: Hot for Teacher
description: Sit start with right hand in the undercling and left on the pad only pocket. Pull up hard and throw for the ledge under the overhang. Get high feet and gain a jug. Then you're home free.

name: Isolation Arete
description: Sit start on a good flake, move left into a good slot, keep working left through big sharp jugs, big slap moves up top on slopers, and finish it out

name: Quarantine Crimp
description: Sit start on small crimpy pockets right in the middle of the wall, big move to the break, another big move to the lip and a good incut up and right, balancey top out watch out for trees

name: Skoolyard Bully
description: Like all schoolyard bullies it's all hard until you throw down. After a few short moves it punks out.  Sitting start with your right foot the quarter thick edge and your left on the angling foot chip. Right hand on the angling flake and left on the low crimp. Bump get a high left foot, bump to the angled edge then throw for the sloper under the overhang. After this you should be home free and your bully cowering in the corner.

name: Smoking In The Boys Room
description: Start Low on two small pockets with good feet underneath the overhang. Use some crimps and a slopy ledge to set up for a dynamic move to a jug on the next ledge.

name: Buffalo Head
description: Sit start under the Buffalo's Head. Gain the ledge and work up and over the roof, with a high right heel hook, pulling two pockets and ledges with the left hand. Pull hard and top out.

name: Buffalo Layback
description: Sit Start as low as possible. Gain horizontal lip under the roof, then layback the pronounced sidepull overhead. High left foot and pull the top out.

name: Buffalo Shoulder
description: Left Twin. Left side. Arete feature looks like a Buffalo's Head sticking out to the left.  This route starts under the Buffalo Head and raps around to the right side, scaling up the Buffalo's Shoulder. Nice lateral movement. Jugs, with a small roof and high heel hook practice.

name: Chief Slap-a-hold
description: Sometimes you just gotta slap-a-hold. Sit start with your hands on the good holds and pull up to slap the arete. Then bump your hand up until you can get the side cling with your right hand.

name: Deep in the Swamp
description: Wall on the left side of the dihedral. Sit start. Couple of side pulls, and a great pinch in the middle of the route. Left heel hook in the upper left hand gully & mantle top out.

name: Exiting Stage Left
description: Sit start. Traverse up and left, gaining two side pulls with the left hand. High feet and throw for the lip.  Mantle topout.

name: Swamp Arete
description: Sit Start low on jugs. Move to Underclings on arete Work your way up arete better holds on left side to jugs at the top. Good movement One of the best lines on the boulder.

name: Swamp Pull
description: Sit Start on two big side pulls work up to the top arete feature. Eliminate all the stuff to the right for a slightly harder climb.

name: Swamp Thing
description: Sit start with hands in the horizontal crack. Pull on good holds for an easy top out.

name: Swamp Traverse
description: Sit start on Swamp Pull Make the crux move low and left through a crimp. Continue left avoiding the holds at the top of the boulder. Fight the pump and finish about 4 feet left of Tree frog on obvious lay back feature with jugs.

name: Swamp's Deep Dihedral
description: Climb the center of the mossy, tight dihedral.

name: The Swamp's Gills
description: Climb the gills.

name: That ain't no lie
description: Sit start with your hands in the horizontal crack. Then lay back the crack (or not) until you reach good holds to a nice top out.

name: Tree Frog
description: Same sit start as aint no lie but move up and left into two good holds. keep left to a slopey shallow hold. use the side pull out left if needed and go to the top.

name: Don't Come Aknocking
description: Make your way along the left side of the boulder using the left side of the boulder and the pocket under the roof.

name: The Alveolar Ridge
description: Crux: the last few moves - finding how to move over into the drainage section to pull the lip. Movement is great - forcing good utilization of heals and toes. Holds can be dirty and hard to see, so brush and mark to optimize the send.

name: Ataraxia
description: Pretty well-sustained on slopers. Choreographing the correct hand/heel placement may take a few attempts, but it’s a fairly straightforward climb up to the final holds.

name: Innervated by...
description: Sit start, and climb the rightmost ramp of the cave. No defining crux. Broken into 3 main portions: bumping to a crimp so you can drop your body down, climbing your hands up the sloppy ramp toward the finish, and keeping your feet on the wall to before pulling the lip. Fun movement with fun holds the whole way.

name: Slippery When Wet
description: Good foot work to move you out in order to walk your hands up the rail is the only trick!

name: Snail Trail
description: Start in the hueco on the left wall of the cave, pull your feet on, then bump out to the lip. 1st crux is moving from this position into a spot where you can continue up and right along the rim. Same top-out as “Ataraxia”.

name: The J-Hole
description: I assume I'm not the first person to do this, but I didn't see it so I'm claiming it. Also, I'm not heavily familiar with the bouldering rating system. I figured V4 was ballpark of what it was, but it may be easier or harder. I'm not an avid boulderer, but it took me multiple tries and I was successful after 15 minutes or so. I also rated it as great, just because it was quite fun. You may not agree.There is a cool little mini-cave, in a rock cliff on the water. Note that the water may be higher or lower, so the difficulty may decrease (higher water) or increase (lower water). If you start from a boat, it will be V0 and you'll be lame. I wore a life vest. It may be a little easier to get out of the water without it, but it does help if/when you fall back into it.Start in the water. There are a couple good hand holds that you can reach from the water. Pull up and you'll be able to get a foot planted (keep in mind that your feet are still in the water, so it will be a little slippery - I wore Vibram FiveFingers). There is a dry vertical ledge, at the right, that you can press your right foot against. There is a vertical ledge, above your right foot, that you can grab to create opposite pressure. There is a knob, above and to the left, and a couple small shelves to work with. End up in the J-Hole. The crux is getting your body out of the water.Alternatively, there is a cool-looking crack on the left side that goes up and above the J-Hole. That would be another entry, though.

name: Extension Invention
description: Same start as pistol grip pump but at the flake break left to a deep pocket. Linkup with Ain't Gonna be pretty on left side.

name: Natural D's
description: A long, obvious endurance line out the cave. A couple of hard moves lead to a core-intensive rest and another hard sequence on a big undercling and crimp rail. Top out via V2-ish climbing. An epic journey of a boulder problem, certain to cater to route climbers. To my understanding, V7 is the grade the FA proposed. 5.12b or 5.12c seem just as appropriate

name: The Nemesis
description: You'll never believe it, but this is another long endurance line in the cave. Shares the same start as Triple/Natural D's, Training Wheels, and Finders & Repeaters, then branches right and takes on the right side of the central prow. This is the longest and most enduro line that starts on the common start. Excellent rock quality and movement, various rests, and the sky is the limit on how creative you can get with your beta.

name: Pistol Grip Pump
description: Super fun, powerful climbing on ergonomic pockets with many options for beta.

name: Dolly Parton
description: Same sit start as Softball. Work right on slopers to lip. Top out right of the tree.

name: The Head
description: Left of softball. SDS, work your way up the bulge or head and topout.

name: Pinch the Weiner
description: Starts on the pinch under the roof, work your way out right using the arete, cave crimps, etc.

name: Softball
description: SDS on shelf to right, work your way left to pinch and crimps. Follow slopey rails to topout. Reach for the softball!

name: 6 oz.
description: The white arete/face directly right of Muggy Situation. Start under roof on holds, work out to shelf, to several moves on slopey crimps to the horn and crimps for topout. Scary beginning moves. The fall from the crux (crimps) is a flat landing.

name: Big Toe
description: Starts under the roof and works the right arete to the face, hold the compression moves and topout on slopers

name: Bliss Jump
description: To the right of Walking on Thin Ice. Starts on a hold on the lip of the roof. jump and work your way on slopers straight up. There is a climb going left from the start hold as well.

name: Dirk Nowitzki
description: On the same overhanging bulge as Trees Off, Dan but starts and stays on the right side of the tree. Start low and work up overhang. Cool pinch and crimps lead to a slopey topout

name: Drinking Out of Cups
description: Right of Chicken Sandwich. Start on jug, work up and left to slopers, fire to crimp, topout. Sweet climb!

name: Dry Dreams
description: To the right of Jabba. Stand start and work your way left on arete. Get to slopers and follow the water drainage up.

name: Electrons
description: Starts on obvious jugs in roof, right of Flying Man Dude. Same start as "Grounds Off, Lance". Undercling to a jug and work left once at the lip. after traversing left topout on the far arete.

name: Flying Man Dude
description: Start on obvious holds and work up in the roof on pockets, top out on slopers. For the v4 grade, stay right of the crack.

name: Frost Traverse
description: Start on Swinging Machete & end to the right of Flying Man Dude. The stand start v6, starts on Dry Dreams & ends out right of Flying....

name: Grounds Off, Lance
description: To the right of Flying Dude Man. Starts up in the roof on an undercling, make a big move out to jug and work your way right to topout.

name: Inamorata
description: Same start as Turn of the Screw instead work left into pockets once in the roof and topout of My Mistress / Grounds Off, Lance.

name: Jabba the Hut
description: Start on a jug under the large roof.  Follow the sloping shelves slightly right out to the lip and top out

name: Mind Games
description: To the right of Muggy Situation. Start up under roof on tooth. Work your way on the roof through crimps and finger jams in crack. Leap for jug, hold the scary swing as you are already 10ft off the ground! Move to obvious slopers, arete and nipple at top. You got balls.....we will see.

name: Muggy Situation
description: To the right of Perfect Spotter. Huge arete. Start on the left side and work your way through slopey crimps to the jug horn on the arete. After that is some heady but easy arete climbing. *** You can also climb the face to the left of the arete for a "Wild Ride". Pretty heady & good!!

name: My Mistress
description: To the left of Turn of the Screw. Stand start on crimps. Move into pockets, lunge for gaston, go to jug and top out left. v8/9 AKA The Beast

name: Perfect Spotter
description: Walk to the right of Bliss Jump. Starts on shelf on the roof, work your way on shelf to slopers and top out. The tree makes for a good spot. **There is another jump start in between the two climbs as well as a hard dyno project.

name: Swinging Machete
description: Left of Jabba the Hut. Starts on tooth, climb in roof and work your way out to good holds. Topout to left. Classic.

name: Tinactin
description: Start on chalked shelf and trend right onto positive edges and jugs of left side of roof. Top out.

name: Trees Off, Dan
description: To the right of Mind Games!!! Found on obvious overhanging bulge. Start low and work through slopey rails, crimps and a high foot for the topout

name: Turn of the Screw
description: To the right of Grounds Off, Lance. Stand start on sidepull jug. Work your way up to swiss cheese holds up in the roof. Hold the swing and topout on this heady classic!

name: Walking on Thin Ice
description: To the right of turn of the screw. squat start on bad crimps...move out left to shelf, work your way up the slopey topout.

name: Farkle Arete
description: Start far left on good jug and trend right on arete and underclings to top out on highest point of boulder.

name: Nombre Absurdo
description: Starts just left of Turtle.  Sit start under roof on a jug. use undercling pinch, large move at the lip

name: Turtle
description: climbs the left side of the turtle neck

name: Turtle of the Night
description: same start as turtle head. After the move to the lip traverse right across the seam into woodland prostitute(V5).

name: Turtlehead
description: SDS on shelf below Turtle Head...work your way to pinch, pocket and out to shelf. Go straight up and top out on the turtle head...

name: Woodland prostitute
description: sit start on right facing crimp rail under the lip work up the arete trending left for top out.

name: Rick James
description: Sit start in small cave, work out on rail to big slopers finish with a mantle

name: Slam dunk
description: Sit start low and pull a few crimps to the “slam dunk” then top out.

name: Toe-bi
description: Mid way up the route there is an interesting under-cling match to navigate against the face to the top out.

name: Under over pass
description: A large boulder that locals use to jump into the water, towards the right hand side of the boulder facing the water there is an amazing over hanging edge. Start low near the water and climb your way up under the ledge and navigate over the lip (v1-v2). From here it is a very easy (v-easy) climb up the remaining of the problem.

name: Fumunda
description: Found to the right of the cave. SDS on the flat rock found in the overhang towards the back. Traverse out of the overhang and climb the cliff about 10 ft up.

name: Strong man Traverse
description: Starts at the outside of the overhang to the right of Fumunda. Starts on jugs and traverses right as far as you want.

name: Upsidedown Plate
description: Found to the left of the overhang. Boulder looks like an upsidedown plate and the problem is in between 2 boulders. SDS-top out.

name: Why
description: Found to the left of Strong Man. Starts on jugs, traverses left and top out. Nice jugs but is a challenge.

name: 8 legged friend
description: Fun warmup!

name: Conspiracy theories
description: Small crimp undercling in the “mouth”. Plenty of good pockets

name: Dirty Mouth
description: Start tucked under the roof on a shoulder press with good feet. Traverse left and then up through the overhanging dihedral to the sloper. Crux is the move to the lip. Fun, easy top out. Best problem at the hollow.

name: Express Rail
description: start on left rail and work way across then up.

name: The Mayflower
description: Fun sit start to a nice ledge. Work through holds with good feet. The Crux is working up the feet to make a reachy move off the side pull. Top out to the right. Might need cleaning at the top, but worth the effort.

name: Octoepus
description: Start on the lowest two finger pockets

name: Pockets
description: look at photo

name: Stretch Armstong
description: This is a super reachy route a few decent holds, but mainly crimps.

name: Two Pump Shimmy
description: Start on low jug and two big pump moves to the top. Top isn't shown.

name: Across the Choss
description: Start on "Campbell"   and after the second bolt traverse left across the wall following 7 wave bolts to the anchors of "Lefty"    The route is mostly clean though the black section is especially chossy and dirty even by Cliff Drive standards.     Great for multipitch practice, though a 40m will be enough to lower the leader back to the ground.

name: Alphonsus
description: Somewhat tricky scramble to the small ledge for the first clip. Climbing the right side of bolt line, there’s a small flake, climbing on the left side, there are some rounded ledges and and a few crimps. The crux is between clips 1 and 2.In memoriam of Evan Patrick Alphonsus Harkins, who got his whole family into climbing.

name: The Big Crack
description: Climb the twin crack system.  Fun.

name: Campbell
description: Either stick clip or scramble up the small ledge to reach for the first bolt. Then move left and up with the flake for two more. After clipping the third bolt traverse through a short crux right and up to the anchors.

name: El Sasa Beach
description: Start at a broken ledge and then work with hidden holds on less than vertical terrain to a crux before the third bolt. Tricky sloppers and crimps give way to solid jugs and slightly more than vertical climbing to the anchors.     Named after the scummiest beach of South Africa.

name: Five Times Fast
description: Start at a broken ledge and work straight up a few crimps and solid jugs to a sweet mega jug at the 3rd bolt. Move through cool side-pulls, under clings, and more jugs to the anchors.

name: Lefty
description: Fun moderate climb. Bouldery start with some more difficult moves 10 feet from the top.

name: McGee
description: Climb the first half of "the Flake". After the second bolt head up and left onto the face.     Most the route is about 5.6. The pronounced crux is one or two moves after the second bolt. Hit the third and traverse left to the anchors of "Campbell"

name: Righty
description: Start with a high hand match on the ledge a few feet below the first bolt. Stay on or slightly right of the bolt line before the big ledge. Avoid using the crack to the left of the route. The fifth bolt is a glue-in just above the big ledge and is optional. Be careful when clipping the anchors as a fall could land on the big ledge.

name: The Small Crack
description: Climb the broken finger crack in the dihedral.

name: Blimp
description: Blimp is the arete right of The Book. The start of this route is kind of a pain with slippery foot holds and some loose rock. Don't blow it clipping the second bolt. If you do fall while clipping the second bolt it could very well be a ground fall and a twisted ankle due to the not-so-flat-landing, plan accordingly. The second half of the route is still challenging but offers some more solid rock and foot placements with some interesting moves and some exciting exposure.

name: Book Right Wall
description: Climb only the right hand wall of the book.  Sounds contrived but is actually a good route considering how few routes are available in the area.

name: The Book
description: This is the polished left-facing dihedral crack.

name: Fun Fiery Blimb
description: Interesting leftward linkup going past two or three bolts of Fun Wall, through a big flake, connecting a single bolt to Under Fire's anchors and onward over run-out chose to The Blimp's anchors.

name: Funwall
description: Start on top of the detached flake on the bottom for a 5.6 climb or start left of the flake for a more difficult slick, dusty climb. Climbing over the detached flake could result in a bad fall onto the flake.

name: Holmes
description: Starts just left of "The Book" dihedral / crack.  Quest up the solid but dirty rock.

name: Under Fire
description: Easy climbing to a ledge and high first bolt leads to sequential moves and technical climbing up a slightly overhanging face.

name: Walk Up
description: Climb the manmade ledge system at the far right end of the crag, two gullies right of the Book.  At the top, a trail leads all the way to the left end of teh crag.  Be careful.

name: Desiccation
description: Desiccation is the face climb just right of the dihedral. Left wall is considered off. Don't plan to fall off this problem, its a bit high. Presently dirty finger/hand cracks lead to a side pull to the top. Your already pretty high by the time you get up there so top out.

name: Hawt Pockets
description: Sit start on the two pockets 3 feet off the ground. Go straight up.

name: Scared Sitless
description: Start standing four feet left of Hawt Pockets. Go up and a little left to that thin pocket then continue up and right. Top out using tree to the left or down climb once you reach the top.

name: Scolopendra
description: Sit Start if possible with the two finger pocket and any holds below it. Then move up and right a bit on crimpers. Finish on easy holds up and left.   Don't use that hold next to the crack about 6 feet off the ground.

name: The Detonate Flake
description: Layback the flake until you come to the block with a hole you can sling go left and up to the tree. Rock seems solid but decide that for yourself.

name: Voldemort and the Manwich
description: Fun route with spaced and marginal protection which involves surmounting two small roofs. Starts underneath the pocket/slit and ends standing on top of the second roof. Rated PG13 for ground fall potential between 1st and 2nd pro placements as well as somewhat tricky gear. A bat might live in that pocket so don't stick you're fingers in there.    The route is dirty and may have some loose rock on it as well. With time it will clean up well. Such is Cliff Drive's finestone.

name: The Bolt Route
description: Start on the crimp and pull into the pocket.  Note the foot under the roof for the next moves.  Continue up and left to the 2nd bolt, then back right and up after the 3rd bolt.  Shares anchors with Subtle Caress on the right.    You can climb up and right past the first anchors for more 12a climbing.  One more bolt over the roof and a second set of anchors.

name: Bovine Blowout
description: Climb the first 3 bolts of Bovine Direct, the farthest route right on the Overhang.  Then continue up and left past another bolt.  Either clip the last bolt on Sea of Cheez and continue to its anchors or head back right to the anchors on Bovine Direct.

name: Bovine Direct
description: Easier face climbing leads to small crimp undercling to pull the roof.  Then angle up and left to the anchors on easier holds.

name: Chomping the Bit
description: Start right of the crack and head up on face holds to the arete/dihedral.  A little chossy left around the corner after the 3rd bolt.

name: Fists Hands Fingers and Jams
description: Climb the short 5.7 crack 10 feet to the ledge. Follow the 5.6 dihedral all the way until the crack ends. Don't climb on the dangerous loose choss to the right of the dihedral. Fun route, just a little dirty.

name: Malaria
description: Easier face climbing takes you up to the sequential and interesting crux section.  The anchors are under the large roof.

name: Malarial Caress
description: A nice linkup with delicate thin moves, some call it the Cataluna of Kansas City.  Linkup:  First two bolts of Subtle Caress, 3rd bolt of The Bolt Route, 4th bolt to end of Malaria

name: Malarious
description: After clipping the anchor(s) of "Chomping the Bit" go up and right onto sharp holds past one bolt up to the anchors of Malaria.    A kneebar is possible once you step onto the final jug of chomping the bit. Go past one bolt followed by crimpers then continue to the anchors. Choose one of two final holds, one directly below the anchor which requires an awkward body position to clip on, or go up and left of the anchors onto a jug.    The route was added in winter of 2012-13 by adding a single bolt between the anchors of Chomping the Bit and Malaria. Best use of a single bolt ever.

name: Sea of Cheez
description: Fun overhanging face climb with a very high first bolt.  It's easy to the bolt, though.  After clipping the third draw, begin heading up and right to turn the roof for the finish.  The clipping holds can be muddy if it has been raining recently.  If not, they are typically covered in a slick film of dirt.

name: Subtle Caress
description: Meanders a little.  Sustained climbing through roof midway up, then up and left to share anchors with the Bolt Route.  Big moves.

name: Tattoo
description: For historical completeness, this was the first route done without bolts or top rope on the overhang. It goes directly through the stacked blocks in the center of the overhang. The crux is being able to stand on the blocks then moving up to the left side of the small cave above. A knee bar in the cave gives a great rest before the final moves. On the topo it is between routes 5 and 6.   I understand this route has now been bolted so I changed it to a sport route  (I haven't personally been back to see).    When I soloed it, there were no bolts anywhere on cliff drive.   Times have changed as has the slickness of the rock I hear.

name: UK Belly Button Flake
description: This choss pile was first climbed in the fog and rain up to the belly button and through the large hollow death flake above it.    All the rock and gear placements above the belly button cave are marginal at the very best. You can see through the flake and feel it flex after you stand up on it.

name: Chief Monegaw
description: Start at the base of the zig zagging flake. A few big moves gets you to the massive roof. Pull over the roof with a few powerful moves. Mantle up the tiered ledges for a thin finish.

name: Dawn Coyote
description: Stick clip, then execute a strange technical sequence on sugary rock to jugs and a second bolt. A powerful jug-to-jug deadpoint gains the third bolt and a good rest. Execute a V4 boulder problem or dyno through, and mantle over a ledge into a no-hands rest. Solve two more short problems separated by a ledge. Were this route not interrupted by two no-hands rests, it would be 4 stars and one of the best routes in the state.

name: North of the North Fourty
description: North 40-esque 10a

name: Pinkerton
description: Easy climbing left of the cave leads to a standing rest. Bust a bouldery move and hang on until the chains.

name: Planet of Sound
description: Left of Wayne Burnside, climb to roof and make a couple powerful overhung moves to surmount the tiered roof, cruise to top

name: The Resistance
description: Campus start from a jug pocket, and work your way through the bulge on good holds. Two mantels and the beautiful arete finish make it worth your while.

name: Ring of Fire
description: Right of the cave. There is a particular clip that must be approached with caution above the midway ledge.

name: Train Gang
description: Stick clip the first bolt, for full points create a rock stack on the left side of the cave, starting on dark black jug pocket. Execute a tough rightward move, past the obvious large scar. A tough move gains the ledge and after a short rest further sustained climbing above.     The guidebook says yard-up to the first bolt, but for full value don't bother.

name: Wayne Burnside
description: Climbs above spray paint name sake. Well featured face follows bolts right of the roof. Make a big move just above the roof up to nice rail. A small hand traverse and crimps lead to chains.

name: Cortez
description: Originally an A2 line climbed Aug 9th 1979 by Kelly Mallicoat and Clint Carriker called Montezuma's Revenge. Cortez, who conquered Montezuma, now goes free.    Climb out the impressive hanging corner utilizing sequential gymnastic beta and pull over the roof on excellent jugs.

name: Fading Glory
description: As you enter the crux of Modern Petroglyph, instead of going up, follow fixed draws across the lip of the roof to the right, pull over onto a face, then up the steep headwall continually angling to the right. A bit of rope drag due to length and changing angles, but back-cleaning a few clips helps.

name: The Grand Finale
description: A Missouri masterpiece, start in a Dihedral leading to an overhanging roof, pull the roof to a standing rest and continue for more overhanging jugs leading to a thin redpoint crux.

name: Grandfather Sky
description: The little, but worthy, brother to "The Grand Finale" Start as for "The Grand Finale", when you pull the first roof trend right towards the bolts without permadraws, continue upward for a nice vertical outing.

name: Love Letter
description: Unfortunately, this climb requires a "trolly start" due to the unclimbable sugar-choss at the base of the route.  Stick clip the first bolt and haul to the near-by jugs.  Past the second bolt,  the climbing is fantastic.  Climb through the crux at the first roof and then rest up before being briefly transported to Sam's Throne on the short, but tricky, headwall.

name: Modern Petroglyph
description: Fun route sharing a start with Love Letter. Stick clip and boink past the choss. Traverse right and up, unclipping and re-racking the first two draws behind you to save on rope drag and ease cleaning. Bust up through the roof on jugs, clip the last permadraw, and collect yourself for a dynamic crux at the lip. Two bolts of easier climbing take you to the chains.

name: Easy Labor
description: Dirty low but good clean 10a climbing on upper portion over green lichen to pocket finish

name: The Eggman
description: Left of the two trees, starts on a bucket jug that leads to sustained excellent vertical climbing.

name: Lone Brave
description: Tough overhanging no feet start to crimpy sustained sequences

name: Manternity
description: Identified by right facing lieback

name: One Shot
description: Sustained, short hand traverse between bolts midway, cool pocket-undercling-pinch finish

name: Arborist Left
description: Follow a left angling slopey rail to a big sidepull jug and top out the easy slab. Quite a good lowball problem.

name: Arborist Right
description: Start on the left side of the undercut on a left angling flake(Arborist Left), heading straight up though amazing slopey grips and eventually grabbing the obvious hueco above the undercut. An exceptionally powerful problem with some really poor holds.

name: Jupiter's Travels
description: Old problem put up several years ago now, just remembering it.   Sit start on right exit of the cave, work up pitch line.

name: Osage Chiefs Center
description: Start as for Osage Chiefs Left on an obvious jug, instead heading right out the sick thin crimp rail, eventually making a big move to a flat, orange jug. Top out the shield as usual. Engaging movement makes up for a relative lack of height.

name: Osage Chiefs Left
description: The easiest line out of the cave. Start low and follow obvious chalked jugs to an exciting topout.

name: Osage Chiefs Right
description: Start on an obvious jug on the far right of the Osage Chiefs undercut. Head left under a hanging orange blocks using small small crimps and cool footwork. Stick a big move to the finishing jug on Osage Chiefs Center and top out.

name: Tree Hugger
description: Start right of the small undercut on an obvious larger hold. Angle up and left to the hueco shared with Arborist right using underclings and crimps on the slab. Requires a good cleaning most of the time.

name: Closed Project
description: Starting off a rockstack, head up on a couple of jugs and then left on pockets to a huge move. Could be 5.11, could be a bit harder. If you're feeling really saucy, a direct start would certainly up the difficulty.

name: Closed Project
description: A powerful V4 boulder problem leads to a pair of pockets on the face. Super ultra thin and sloping crimps take you to a rad, incut pocket and a big dyno to the anchor. This route cuts off before the choss band above it, which would likely decrease the quality of the route. It is possible the extension may be bolted in the future. The grade is a guess, it could be a bit easier or way harder.  The route has not been sent, please do not climb on it for the time being.

name: Forgot The Crashpad
description: Far left route. Blunted arete with 3 bolts up to anchors on a ledge (anchor carabiners hanging over lip on slings).

name: Ibexercise
description: Climb neat jugs and ledges to a break in the rock. A hard, fngery move gets you through the blank section. Top out on the dirty ledge to clip the anchors.

name: Moon Compass
description: A V6 boulder problem leads to nice ledgey steep terrain, pull through the boulder problem and climb at mid 5.11

name: Nineteen Seventy Six
description: Start on the rising, under-cling rail. A handful of strenuous moves to the second bolt comprise the crux.

name: One and One make Eleven
description: A plethora of jugs, edges, and pockets leads to a thin 2-move crux. Bash enormous jugs to the anchors.

name: Quarantina Turner
description: Right side of tree. First clip is high; recommended stick clip. V3 start moves to easier climbing to chains.null

name: Short-N-Stout
description: Fun low crux with several solutions leads to easier terrain working towards an attention-getting finish to the lip.

name: Thats not how you eat a banana
description: Just left of tree, stretchy first move to easier climbing to chains.

name: Thistle Do
description: Float up the low-angle face on comfy crimps and awesome ledges, finishing below the roof.

name: Thistle Don't
description: Just right of Thistle, work up blank slab face towards curved cut in roof. Muscle over roof to the chains.

name: Transcendence
description: Starts in an obvious left-facing chalked flake. Follow a proud line of perfect incut crimps to a huge jump move to the jug pocket. Probably possible to top out but this one is generally done as a drop off.

name: Climbing back to your roots
description: 15 feet west of "Jesse James".  Pull through the overhang to access the vertical crack.

name: Cool August Morning
description: 10 feet east of "Jesse James".  Climb through overhang 10 ft east of Jesse James,  tcu and nuts are handy, then run it out to the obvious finger crack above the horizontal band of jugs, potential ground fall) after the short finger crack traverse to the anchors of Jesse James.  Very run out!

name: Jesse James
description: Brittle and flaky face, left of Zig Zag

name: Paper Tiger
description: Bouldering on a rope, stick clip the first bolt  A few nice holds lead to a thin punishing V6+ boulder problem.  EDIT  somebody has unlocked much easier beta that probably traverses out of the way

name: Zig Zag
description: Description: A nice shorty that follows a zig zag, ragged edge feature. The face holds are bomber, but most of the zig zagging flake is hollow and suspect. Tread carefully.     Location: Identified by the foot thick zig zagging flake that moves up the wall.     Protection: 4 bolts plus 2 bolt anchor with lower offs

name: Ancient Axe
description: One of the more sustained routes at the Fortress. For full value, start low inside cave on a huge jug flake.

name: Billy's Holiday
description: Steeper alternate start to Rockabilly on the left.

name: Edgar Allen Bro
description: Slightly harder start to Native Tongue.

name: Native Tongue
description: Starts on deep left angling flake to a series of fun moves on jugs. Exciting photogenic finish on the tongue feature.

name: Nevermore
description: Shares start with EAB then angles sharp right under a small roof. Getting passed the small roof section is the short exciting crux of this great route.

name: Rockabilly
description: Fun arête with a good rest below an exciting over vertical crux finish to the anchors.

name: Warriors
description: Start on sharp holds and power through a short series of fun sustained moves. The difficulty eases up only slightly after you pass the steep face and near the anchors.

name: Arkasouri
description: Climb up above the left side of the little cave, into a technical vertical face and straight up to the anchors.

name: Captain Bird Beard
description: Start near the water on a small boulder. When flooded start as of Snake & Eggs and traverse in. Climb the beautiful far right arête nearly right over the water.

name: Climbing for Two
description: Grey corner to the left.    First done pregnant.

name: Earth Apple
description: Short route with soft rock on an arête.

name: Firestar
description: White arête on the southwest corner of Goose Island

name: Pirates of the Carabiner
description: Start at the SW corner of Goose Island. Traverse out left to a single bolt belay, then angle up the face and top out.

name: Raven Lunatic
description: Righteous climbing up an arête with a no hands rest before the first crux. Pull sequential moves high up at the second crux to reach the anchor.

name: Snake and Eggs
description: Start right of the little cave on a spine feature. Climb the spine to a ledge and climb straight up the technical face and through a large smooth shoot feature.

name: Todd the Bod
description: This route climbs up broken ledges with awesome solid conglomerate rock.

name: Arrowhead
description: Climb through the super cool huecos and pockets up wonderful sustained moderate climbing. If the start is flooded, traverse in from Turtles of a Shell. First done ground up with traditional pro.

name: Birds of a Feather
description: This is THE line. Ascending the beautiful east edge of the picturesque standalone tower, this route has the best positioning and top-out of any climb at Raven Rocks and arguably the whole state.

name: Deli Faction
description: Starts under the big red mega jug, climbs right across a ledge, and climbs the left side of an arête with sweet features.

name: Iron Bro-ccoli
description: Start at little pocket and trend left to the flake and shattered rock. Finish with some slopers and a series of mantels to the big ledge.

name: Thunderbird
description: Connect cool pinches and features to a flared hand crack then angle right to the anchors of Turtles.

name: Turtles of a Shell
description: Climb the center face aiming towards two separate, left leaning crack features. This was the first route put up at Raven Rocks and was done ground up with traditional pro.

name: The Alchemist
description: One-move-wonder to great climbing above. This would be 3 stars if not for the start.

name: Captain Caveman
description: Climb the face to the left of the cave, heading a little right near the top of the cave to the anchors.  Mostly decent rock.

name: Doctor Krank
description: Thin face climbing on sharp crimps, flakes, and small feet lead to the base of an undercling roof. Pull the roof on good holds into a couple more moves prior to an easy mantle.

name: Inertia
description: Sweet line up center scoop on wall.  Crux fourth bolt may seem a bit high and can benefit from a pre-hung draw.

name: Mighty Joe Knuckles
description: This is the left-most bolted line on Long Dog Wall. Starts off a flake left of the ramp.  Stay left to avoid harder climbing.

name: Mirage
description: Bolted line through roof right of bushy crack. Somewhat contrived at crux.

name: Special K
description: Climb the vertical face above the large flake.  Pretty good rock.

name: Superstition
description: Climbs a seam to face above. Brutal small holds.

name: Billy Bob Bulldozer
description: Climb the low-angled slab to a chossy ledge.  Then continue on better rock through the blocky bulge up high to the anchors.  Half the route is pretty good rock, the other half is pretty chossy.

name: Godspeed
description: Blank face with many unique mini-cruxes right of the Shadow Puppet dihedral.

name: Jeronimo
description: First route right of the cave/alcove. Climb to a roof, then follow the arête/face to anchors.

name: Jr. Bacon Chossburger
description: Face climbing on decent quality vertical rock.

name: Paddlefish
description: Vertical face and steep slab climbing on pretty good rock.  If I remember right, there are both a mono and a cool fingerlock on this route.

name: Phetus Feola
description: Climb the technical vertical face and steep slab above on pretty good rock.

name: Pregnant Fembot
description: Climb the face starting on the left side of the cave and ending on the left side of the bulge at the top.  Pretty good rock.

name: Shadow Puppet
description: Climb past the first few bolts on Jeronimo and step left into the right facing dihedral crack.  Make sure to place long slings before and after going into the corner, as it is sharp.  Follow the dihedral crack up and right.  Where it ends, traverse right to bolted anchors on another route.  Pretty good rock.

name: Shock and Awe
description: Low, tricky crux on face climbing, then sustained at a slightly moderate level.

name: Tick Tattoo
description: Climb the face just right of the small cave, ending on the right side of the bulge at the top.  Pretty good rock.

name: Pockets
description: Powerful moves off a sharp pocket

name: Arabia Aground
description: Tough start leads to several right facing sidepulls/pinches mid route.

name: Bannister Federal
description: Tough hanging start with a fingerlock to crimps. After the jug rail midway try not to stray to the left onto "John Brown".

name: John Brown
description: Bouldery start that leads to crazy melting limestone and a few Tuffas, slightly contrived because of the proximity to "Bannister Federal", stay to the left of the bolt line. Some call it the Oliana of Kansas City.

name: Pendergast
description: Pull the hanging start, work up to a defined razor crimp crux

name: Shawnee Mission Accomplished
description: The obvious crack on the left side of the wall    If you wanted to lead it on gear you could, it would probably take lots of RPs, not recommended.

name: The Lonely China Man
description: A sit start with a low crux. You  follow the vertical crack up to a horizontal ledge, where the problem is finished. It is impossible to top out, due to brush.

name: Nature Sucks
description: A nice sit-start, with aheel hook to pull yourself up to a crack, where you can then top out.

name: KC High Ball
description: High ball problem. Flat landing, but you'll want spotters to stop you if you roll or the tress can do the job. I did it today just fine and love the view from the top. At least 18ft.

name: The Last Rhino
description: Classic problem here. Hard and skin-taxing.

name: Arise and Shine
description: Bust a couple tough intro moves on crimps and pockets, set up, and bust a big move for the lip. Easy topout.

name: Thermometer
description: A nice line of pockets heading up the left side of the face, but not up the arete, which is V3. Any beta I tried that eventally led me to the obvious "thermometer" hold seemed V4ish. Not as good as Arise and Shine, but still a fun line.

name: Cabin Fever
description: Stand start on small underclings and chossy feet. The first move is probably out left to a juggy undercling/sidepull. Make a couple hard moves to establish right hand on the obvious slopey rail/arete and top out. Fun compression line, and a novel style for the area. Good movement compensates a bit for some really chossy rock down low.

name: Dactyloid
description: We stopped here on a cross-country roadtrip at the recommendation of several locals, including Dick Dower, who discovered this area and had a good time climbing with our two small children. After doing all the established problems and not wanting to quite get back in the car, I played around with this traverse along the base.   Sit start on the far left side and work your way rightward, staying low (below the juggy shelf/break below the overhang). This can be made harder or easier depending on which holds you decide are "on" or not. In general I found the rock to be a bit more solid than the topouts on all the other established problems and so ended up doing it several times (including right to left) before we moved on. Top out on the right side, either via D'Horn or D1.

name: Big Boy
description: Long crack slopers into overhang.

name: Poolside
description: Great line on ridge of roof.

name: Back Bend
description: This boulder may not look like much, but it a great boulder. Awesome hard sloper topout and will make you press your stomach as hard as you can into the rock.

name: Headache
description: ledge sit start to sharp crimps.

name: Cave Area
description: All the way at the end of the trail. Huge area with a lot for potential for harder problems.

name: Chicken Patty
description: Low start. Start holds.

name: Creekside Crack
description: Little crack in the Creek side area to practice laybacks and even a foot jam or two.

name: Jerk Chicken
description: Fun boulder problem with sharp holds and scary top-out. Also one of the highest boulders in Swope.

name: Man on a Ledge
description: Sit start to small flake, match there and then dyno to top or pull on small crimp.

name: Cafeteria Brawl
description: Refer to photo

name: Doin' Time
description: Sit-start; climb the obvious zig-zig crack.

name: Hard Labor
description: refer to photo

name: Time Bandit
description: Fun climb, don't use the wall behind you.

name: Fox Hollow Roof
description: Start under the roof on the horizontal line, then straight out to the lip to up and over.

name: Fox Hollow Roof
description: Follow trail. Trails maps are offered in the nature center. Great roof problem with rock that is actually solid

name: The Keyhole
description: Sit start, the name should give it away.

name: The Scoop
description: Fun climb, nasty tree up top. Once you get there you've beat the climb.

name: Thirsty Soul
description: Sit start just left of the arete, stay on the face.

name: Cracker Smack
description: On the corridor side of the boulder, this is the thin crack.  Without the face holds, it is V1.

name: Graffiti Pete
description: On the corridor side of the boulder, this is the face right of the thin crack.

name: The Pillar Arete
description: Climb the right side of the arete where the corridor and the wall that faces the road come together.

name: Slime Time
description: On the corridor side of the boulder, this is the face left of the thin crack.

name: Round House
description: Sit-down-start; begin on the horizontal crack on the far right side of the boulder. Bump to the jagged finger crack and then a series of good crimps before topping out.

name: The Bulge
description: A very fun problem. Sit start matched on an obvious undercling tufa and huge feet. Work up through a jug rail, a crimp, and huck for the top. Fun and brief.

name: Look Sharp
description: Hard problem sharing a start with The Bulge. Start matched on the undercling tufa and work right on small underclings and huge feet. Head straight up just left of the (dead) tree on poor holds. Stay out of the big holds on the arete.

name: Evolution
description: Crimps on decent rock just right of the middle of the face facing the rail problem on No Hands Boulder.

name: Other Half
description: Traverse with your heel and pull your way up to the first ledge. Possibilities to continue to the top of Choss after a rest but glory is already yours.

name: EcoLiberator
description: A fun problem, one of the best in Swope. Start on an obvious, chalked jug under the roof. Reach over the roof using an awesome sloper and a few crimps/sidepulls. Figure out where your feet belong and stick the "dope for swope" crux move. Top out on easy jugs. Low in the grade.

name: Warmup
description: A nice, gently overhanging face with many jugs and slopers. Use whatever holds you want to create warmups for yourself.

name: All Hands
description: Sit start on jugs, do a couple moves on small crimps and dyno to the lip.

name: Cottage Cheese
description: Climb the arete where the slab side and the corridor side come together.

name: Free Hand
description: Cool balancey climbing with a unique move leads to a sharp, technical crux. Bring the skin repair kit or consider tape.

name: Fresh Squeezed Lemon
description: Climb the face and right arete from a sit below the shelf. Going direct through the face is a different problem. Sharp and chossy.

name: Lemon Drop Direct
description: The better line from the Fresh Squeezed Lemon sit start tackles the face left of the arete with crimps and a big move.

name: No Hands Left
description: On the slab side of the boulder, climb the left side of the face using no hands.

name: No Hands Right
description: On the slab side of the boulder, climb the right side of the face using no hands.  Don't forget to top out.

name: The Rail Direct
description: Start 4 feet right of the left corner.  Climb straight up using crimps on the left and the rail on the right.

name: The Rail
description: Start on the right end of the boulder.  Head left and then up and left on the rail to the top left corner of the boulder.

name: Weapons of Mass Creation
description: Hardest line in the OG area, most likely. Start on a big sidepull jug on the left. Traverse along the face into All Hands with whack beta, good feet, and extreme body tension. Getting into position to do the dyno on All Hands is much more engaging with the traverse added in. Not the purest line around, but good rock and movement compensate.

name: Cardiac Arete
description: This is the left corner of the Pocket Boulder.

name: Paper Boy
description: Climb the incut crimps on the right side with awesome feet.

name: The Pocket Route
description: Closer to the right corner of the boulder.  You only get the horizonal crack start and the small 4 inch wide pocket most of the way up.  Sit start.

name: Pooh's Corner
description: This is the low angled arete on the right end of the boulder.  Sit start.

name: Sloping Disappointment
description: Sit start with hands in the horizontal crack.  Bust up on polished slopers and a sidepull.

name: Streaker
description: Climb the leftmost water stain on crimps and underclings.

name: Thumbder Cling
description: On the left side of the main face.  The face right of the water streak.  Sit start.

name: Turkey Blaster
description: On the left side of the boulder, around the corner from the main face.  Climb the face left of the corner.

name: Hans & Frans
description: Start left and then move right using heel-hooks and move around the boulder for top-out.

name: Lip Job
description: A fun eliminate. Start in a low bucket and reach out to a good pocket. Traverse the lip out to top out on the point of the prow, avoiding the jug rail a foot or so above the lip in favor of crimps and slopers

name: Saddle Sore
description: Sit down, then compression moves to the top.

name: Dano
description: Climbs the face between Seam As It Ever Was and Peter Pan on extremely sharp crimps and an undercling.  Sit start.

name: Not Chocolate
description: Climb the right arete, just right of the wide crack.  Sit start.

name: Peter Pan in a Porn Star
description: Climbs the obvious wide crack.

name: Piravida
description: Start on crimp in the middle of the wall with both hands, do a hard pull-up to establish your feet on the wall. Dyno to the top.

name: Seam As It Ever Was
description: Climb the dihedral using the thin seam and crimps.  Sit start.

name: Tree Route
description: Climb the face just right of the tree.  Sit start.

name: Ring Bearer
description: Giant slab problem right as you enter on the trail to your right. Work it right to left with hard mantle for a finish.

name: Tiny Tom
description: Sit-down-start. Climb up the side side of the roof using prominent holds.

name: Battleship Arete
description: Use the arete to climb up, easy climb and could be done in your street shoes. Great view of the woods from the top.

name: Black Mamba
description: For beta refer to photo. Starts back in the crack and don't use the left wall. Plus feet must stay off bottom rocks

name: Glory Hole Lowball
description: Beta on the photo.

name: Just gettin' worse
description: Start on the far right side at a corner where the boulder is just a few feet high. Start traversing left with a good undercling into a smaller crimp. Easy moves over a wide crack lead to a few sloopy holds. A wide move around the corner leads with a reachy move to the top.

name: Oakwood Roof
description: Beta is on the photo

name: Pluralism
description: Beta on photo. Fun outside problem

name: Dawn Mist
description: Excellent, powerful climbing on good edges. The line faintly traces the arete but not everyone uses holds on the right side of the arete. Tall people can cheat way out left onto slabby rock. for a much easier and lower-quality finish.

name: Deathlands Arete
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Deathlands Ridge Traverse
description: Deathlands boulder, climb the ridge on the far right of the boulder

name: Fecal Attraction
description: Climb onto the choss band and do a move to reach a good four finger pocket. Proceed up the bulge.

name: Fireblast
description: Starts on right side of Deathlands Boulder. Start on slopers, Pull into a juggy underling, mount the slab, climb the ridge like lip of the boulder and top out for Triple Stoop or throw a leg over and top out direct.

name: Frank Finds Boulders
description: Start on a right hand crimp and left hand sloper on the far right side of the roof. Climb left through slopers and crimps to an obvious jug and top out. Excellent movement, and quite stout for the grade.

name: Frank Finds Boulders Extension
description: Climb Frank Finds Boulders to the obvious jug on the lip of the roof. Instead of topping out, head left through a small, sharp intermediate and a slopey rail. Campus or throw a high foot, dunk a perfect jug, and top out left of the tree. 4 star movement, 2 star line.

name: Loaded Diaper
description: Start a perfect incut crimp above head height. Deadpoints and a long reach gets you jugs and the lip.

name: Loaded Diaper Low
description: A lower start to Loaded Diaper. Core-tensiony moves on small holds lead to a big move to the perfect incut start crimp on the original problem. Highly recommended.

name: Lost in the woods
description: Located at the far north end of the cliff. Scramble past the giant detached boulder... Sit start under the roof on good holds, toss right hand to sloped edge, power your way to a good pocket and top out on sculpted jugs.

name: Not So Easy Warm Up
description: Fun movement on solid rock, but unfortunately the problem seems to be perpetually extremely dirty and slick. Squat start on a sloper or sit start slightly lower on a pair of slopey crimps for an extra move. Traverse left through weird, inobvious moves with a surprising amount of footwork, and head straight up left of the tree with a few powerful moves on jugs, grabbing the top of what appears from below to be a loose block (it isn't, hopefully...) and topping out.

name: Project
description: I honestly have no idea how hard this is. This project starts from a sit deep in the cave on an obvious undercling. A very cool intro section (probably hard V7 in itself) leads to an inconceivable move to a fat sloper. What appears to be more core-intensive hard climbing should topout through a small dihedral feature (Garbage in Space V8). A very, very hard problem, with bad feet throughout. Not a bit of bad rock on it, but one of the jugs is very sharp. Consider tape, and possibly a kneepad.

name: The Reef Direct
description: Same start at The Reef, bust tough moves, then shoot up to good incuts and top out.

name: The Reef
description: Begin with RH on small crimp under roof, LH on slopper at the lip. Bust tough moves on crimps, surf right through radical coral crimps and heel hook bodacious barnacles.

name: Snail Trail Sit
description: Starts to the right of the crack just past the detached boulder. Start on lower ledge beneath roof, work out of roof to the right to ledge in the middle of the face, then heel down on the lip, move out to crimp, then power finish to lip.

name: Super Stoop
description: Sit start to triple stoop. Start matched on a sloping diving board like feature. Climb up slopers, then traverse slightly right into triple stoop.

name: Trash Man
description: Sit start on crimps on the lip of small roof. Dead point between prominent finger slots.

name: Triple Stoop
description: Start on good holds on the left side of the boulder, move into a juggy undercling, then commit to the slab above. This line climbs directly up the tallest part of the boulder.

name: Fish and Bits
description: Climb the slab to the first anchor.  To there, it's 5.7.  After that, continue on more slab to the base of the roof finger crack.  Place gear and pull the crack to gain the second anchor for a nice 5.9.  Good rock.

name: Frozen Cheerios
description: Climb the featured slab, maybe getting in occasional pro.  Decent rock.

name: Hardly Tardy Bachelor Party
description: Climb up and left, following bolts and pulling some bulges along the way.  Near the top, head into the right dihedral crack or traverse left into Ultra Pimp for a less 'heady' finish.  Decent rock.

name: Mike's Crack
description: Climb the slabby crack to the vertical dihedral halfway up, the highlight of the climb.  Continue around the right side of the chossy buttress on the left.  Decent rock.

name: Morning Wood
description: Follow Ultra Pimp all the way up to the traverse under the large dihedral roof crack with the dead tree in it.  Instead of traversing, climb this crack.  Be careful not to pull on the tree or it may come out.

name: Reckless Hate
description: 5 bolts lead you out the ceiling of the cave via the obviously line of pockets to the crux just below the craziest mantel at Trappers.   Has fixed draws minus the fifth bolt, anchors have rap rings.  Great place to escape the heat...

name: Shatak
description: TR might be the best option since the bolts and gear placement can be a bit sketchy in spots

name: Ultra Pimp
description: Climb up into the overhanging flake, then head up and right.  After 3 or 4 bolts, head left to a cool finger crack.  Climb up right beneath the large dihedral roof crack with a dead tree in it.  Here, traverse right to another dihedral crack.  Climb it up to the anchors on the left.  Good rock up high.  Pretty good rock in the overhanging flake.

name: Haunted House
description: Follow the dihedral handcrack, stemming and jamming, up decent rock to a short slabby finish.

name: Hollow Weenie
description: Slab and face climb on decent rock.

name: Terror-Dactyl
description: Slab climb to vertical section halfway up.  Pull bulge and head up and left along a cool crack, finishing on more slabby face climbing.  Ok rock.

name: Witch's Tit
description: Climb up the slab to the right side of the roof above on decent rock.

name: King Planet
description: Climb up to the thumb of rock in the dihedral on rock that's not so solid.  Clip two bolts on face climbing to the anchors.  Rock is not so good.

name: Open Season
description: Rated PG because of the poor rock the bolts are in down low.  Climb the dihedral/arete of poor quality rock up to a few interesting moves and better rock near the top.  Mostly poor rock.

name: Prize Posession
description: Follow the bolts up steep face climbing on pockets, mostly, and pulling over a bulge.  Mostly good rock.

name: Blind Date
description: Climb the face up to the base of the roof area on the right.  Pull around the left side of it on chossy rock and to the anchors below the lip.  Pretty good rock until the last 15 feet.

name: Chalk a Khan
description: Low angled slab climbing on decent rock.

name: Crimpers Trap
description: More steep slab/face climbing on pretty good rock.

name: Friend of a Friend
description: Low-angled slab climbing on decent rock.

name: Missoureality
description: Climb the steep stab to the thin crack.  Follow it to the base of the roof.  Then, surmount the roof via the steep handcrack and holds.  Some of the rock at the roof may be a tiny bit chossy, but there is good rock overall.

name: Osceolabotomy
description: Climb the large dihedral, arching left, until you come to the tree about 2/3 up.  Here, traverse left to more holds.  Take these up to the offwidth dihedral, pulling up on the right side.  Mostly good rock.

name: Slab 93
description: Steep slab/face climbing arching to the right.  Be careful going to the anchors, it's a tiny runout.  Pretty good rock.

name: Slab 94
description: Climb the steep slab/face past bolts to the anchors.  Good rock.

name: Snuffy the great
description: 20 yds past missourireality wall, 6 bolts, 2 bolt anchor.  Typical slab start,  follow obvious line to the bulge then climb up and slightly right.

name: Sweet Misery
description: Climb the steep slab/face on good rock to the anchors.

name: Carcass
description: Climb up under the small roof on decent rock, coming kind-of close to Inner Pigeon.  Then, head up and right into the good stuff.  This route is more of the great face climbing and good rock that the Pontoon Wall is known for.  Finish at the anchors of Inner Pigeon.

name: Dawn Patrol
description: Starting in Foxjaw Cave, climb out its right side on fractured rock, then head up.  The rest of the climb consists of fun face climbing on good rock.

name: Deitiphobia
description: Quite a mix of climbing styles.  First, climb up and left through the steep pocketed roof.  From there, head up to the base of the right-arching crack.  Follow it up and right, around a bulge.  From there, finish by heading straight up to the anchors.  Mostly great rock, with a few hollow or fractured sections.

name: Elvis is Dead
description: Climb the face near the corner for some interesting moves.  At the top, pull into and through the dihedral with the block in it, using the cracks or holds.  Mostly good rock.

name: Inner Pigeon
description: Start in the crack beneath the small cave, clipping a hidden bolt right below the cave.  Pull the roof of the cave, then head up right first, then back left on beautiful face moves and pockets.  Great rock.

name: Love Boat
description: Face climb on holds and pockets to the base of the flaring crack.  The rock up until the crack is questionable, especially the rock within the last 10 feet before the crack.  Climb the crack straight up, over a little bulge, and to the anchor below the trees.  The rock in the crack to the anchors is good.

name: Sewage Management
description: Climb the dihedral crack system to the top, pulling a bulge along the way.  Usually dirty, but the rock is pretty good.

name: Turn Your Head and Cough
description: Start in the wide crack, climbing it to a threadable hole.  From there, 5-10 feet of low-angled climbing takes you to the beautiful pocketed face and plenty of awesome moves.  Great rock.

name: Vegas Exodus
description: Pull the small roof, then it's face-climbing time.  After 4 or 5 bolts, head up left into the finger crack dihedral.  Follow this until it ends, pulling a small roof on the right.  Continue on another face past 2 more bolts to the anchors.  Mostly great rock, though a little dirty after the upper roof.

name: Vertical Smile
description: Pull the low overhang and head over left on the rails to the first bolt.  It is definitely recommended to stick-clip the first bolt.  Then head up and left, clipping the slung hole.  Where the wall becomes steep, the line starts arching back right, forming the vertical smile.  This line contains awesome moves on sweet Missouri limestone pockets.  Great rock, especially on the headwall part.

name: The Whigg
description: An old creepy trad climb is now a GREAT sport climb. It now is likely one of the best routes at Trappers Camp, with sustained movement on varying sizes of deep and not so deep inset pockets, a unique techy crux, and great rock.

name: Wishful Sinking
description: Climb the face on decent rock, arching right above Foxjaw Cave.  At the one of the two last bolts, either climb to the top on dirt and through trees or traverse right under a mini roof to Dawn Patrol's anchors.

name: Centipede
description: Generic slab climbing through the horizontal line of pockets halfway up.  Good rock.

name: Ghetto Booty
description: Good steep slab/face climbing on mostly good rock.  The sling before the first bolt may be old, so bring your own.

name: Hunky Dory
description: More steep slab/face climbing on pretty good rock.

name: Lo and Behold
description: Great face climbing through bulges on good holds.

name: Logan
description: Steep slab climbing on good rock.

name: Mental Hygiene
description: Climb the face to the crack.  Climb the crack to its end, then traverse right ot the anchors on Rattler.  Pretty good rock.

name: Raider's of the Chossed Arc
description: Climb the slab beneath the left angling dihedral that becomes an undercling roof. Take advantage of pro before getting to the crack. Start working a hand traverse under the roof and navigate through loose, dirty rock eventually joining the anchors for Logan.

name: Rattler
description: Nice moves up vertical face.  Good rock on the route, choss above it.

name: Soup
description: More slab climbing through the horizontal line of pockets.  Good rock.

name: Unsolved Mr E
description: Climb the slab to the base of the headwall.  If you hug the left arete, it's 5.9.  If you stick to the face, it's more like 5.10b.  Pretty good rock.

name: Crisis of Belief
description: Climb the slab to the roof.  Pull the roof and gain a small ledge.  From there, follow the crack to where it peters out, then head left and up for more slab climbing.  Good rock.

name: Enter the Dragon
description: Climb the steep slab in a direct line to the anchor.  Good rock, classic route.

name: Guillotine
description: Climb slab to the right arching flake with the wide crack behind it.  Layback the flake (careful, it's brittle limestone) and finish by angling right on a slab.  Ok rock.

name: New Directions
description: Climb through choss down low to 2 pods side by side. Face/slab on good rock, angling left, to the anchors. Be careful coming down as you will lower through a very loose section.

name: Rowdy Redneck
description: Follow the bolts up the steep crimpy slab and face.  Good rock.

name: The Saint
description: Start on the slab, clipping one bolt on the way to the crack.  Climb the crack to the left, around the bulge, past the tree and to the anchor.  Good rock, excellent climb.  This has been the first trad climb for many MO climbers.

name: Sibling Satellite
description: Climb the slab to the roof, past 2 large huecos and more steep slab to the anchors.  Good rock.

name: Sketch Artist
description: Exit the small cave on the left and follow the thin crack up and left on bad rock to its end.  Then head left to New Directions' anchor on bad runout slabbiness.

name: Loch Ness Tea Plunge
description: P1:  5.6  Head left from the ledge, staying below the roof the whole time.  This reqires some up and down movement, though.  Just aim for the best pro and holds, which aren't that good.  End at 2 bolt anchor below roof dihedral.    P2:  5.9  Clip a bolt or two as you head up and right, over the roof into the dihedral hand crack.  This dihedral can be bushy.  Head straight up the crack to a 2 bolt anchor.    P3:  5.4  Head down and right, around a corner and below a roof.  Head up and left, finally scrambling for the anchors above Haunted House.

name: AtmosFear
description: Long bolted face to the right of Black Snake Crack.

name: Black Snake Crack
description: Pull the dihedral roof on a finger crack.  Then continue up following the crack as it arches to the right near the top.  Pretty good rock.

name: Running From Voodoo
description: To the right of AtmosFear and left of Pressing Shish. Start in vertical scoop, and escape out the right side. Follow bolts and a pin through upper bulge, which leads into a layback crack.

name: Double Undercling
description: Climb the slabby section down low and a vertical section containing the double undercling.  Head up and right through the big roof, then up through a smaller bulge and to the anchors.  Mostly good rock, though a little broken near the roofs.

name: No Such Thing as Spring
description: Climb up the slab to the base of a vertical section containing a finger crack.  Climb it, then head up and left in the hand crack.  After pulling around the corner, head up on bad rock to the top.  Belay on trees.

name: Phantom Fugitives
description: Probably my favorite route in Missouri!    After clipping the first bolt, climb the mini roof dihedral up and left to a ledge.  Then head up and a little right on face climbing.  Some of this section is not very good quality rock, but it's ok.  Aim for the base of the clean dihedral/roof about 50 feet up.  There, pull left into the dihedral/roof.  After getting up a little, head back right and up to the anchors on a ledge.  See note in pro section about descent and cleaning.  Most of the climb has great rock.

name: Yahoo Crack
description: Climb through the chimney like crack in the roof, clipping a bolt above and gaining the ledge.  Continue in the dihedral crack to the anchors halfway up the cliff.  OK rock.

name: Yahoo Crack Extension
description: After climbing Yahoo Crack, angle up and right on face holds, pulling a small roof 10 feet past the first anchor.  After that, more slab/face climbing takes you to the second anchor.  Ok rock.

name: BatStroke
description: To the right of Tomiko on a nice gray face, start with a bolt right off the ground then trend up and right, following 7 bolts.

name: Bottom Rocket
description: This is a choss pile and should only be used to access Pocket Rocket above.  Just follow the bolts.

name: Dogfish
description: Clip the first bolt and work around the left side of the very chossy section to gain the ledge.  Here, the climb may be considered a little runout because if you fail to clip the second bolt, you will deck.  From the ledge, head up on pretty good rock and enjoyable face climbing, pulling a small roof along the way.

name: Funhouse
description: Start on thin vertical/slabby face climbing, heading left near the top of the first section.  Head back right as you scramble up to the base of the headwall.  Then, head up on excellent moves and good rock past 3 or 4 bolts.

name: Ginger Snatch
description: I start on Tigerbill, heading right when it gets slabby.  Whatever way you choose, you need to end up at the base of the steep left-angling hand crack.  Some nice steep crack moves take you to a small tree.  Sling it and head right to the bolts.  Good rock, if you go this way.

name: Gomer Pile
description: Climb hand crack low for 30 feet, stay left at the tree into the crux offwidth to slab finish.

name: Gomerwood
description: Climb the right of the dihedral a few feet to gain the finger crack to the left.  Follow this up to the first bolt.  Then climb the face and slab to the anchors.  Good rock.

name: Saint Judy
description: Start on Tigerbill on the far left ledge of the funhouse alcove. Follow to it's fourth bolt, then merg right onto steep white blocks over a cave. Numerous technical moves lead to an exciting finish.

name: TigerBill
description: Steep prow at far left side of Funhouse alcove. Mostly casual climbing to a short V6 crux. Sends have generally skipped the mid crux bolt as it interrupts the climbing but makes for a good means to hangdog/work it.

name: Tomiko
description: Climb the dihedral hand crack until you can step right onto the face about 1/3 of the way up.  Face climb the rest of the way, folowing the bolts.  Good rock.

name: Camel Toe
description: 11d/12a (see below)    Starts on a slightly overhung face/corner, climbing up into the layback face with the small ledge for feet.  Pull a bulge and climb the steep slab through a slightly chossy section and a scary-to-clip bolt.  Make a hard undercling move to jug pockets.  Steep pockets and sidepulls take you to thin moves at the top.    Holds have fallen off this route over the years.  Stay left at the 4th bolt, as some huge stuff has fallen off there.      Also, the top seems to be missing a hold, but it still goes.  This move and the undercling move below seem a bit easier for taller folks, leading me to suggest 11d/12a, as the crux move felt just as hard as Warrior Poet and Atmosfear (5'9").

name: Droopy Corndog
